1
00:00:00,040 --> 00:00:02,080
CEOs in the physical world don't dare to gamble.

2
00:00:02,080 --> 00:00:03,460
I guess I'm just a bit bolder.

3
00:00:03,460 --> 00:00:05,280
We made a huge gamble.

4
00:00:05,280 --> 00:00:08,589
So we just shut down our entire previous system.

5
00:00:08,589 --> 00:00:10,469
And that system cost us several billion.

6
00:00:10,469 --> 00:00:13,329
Intuitively, what would be a downside of He Xiaopeng's skillset?

7
00:00:13,329 --> 00:00:15,510
I think, once you break down anyone's skills,

8
00:00:15,510 --> 00:00:18,630
you'll find that this person actually has a lot of shortcomings.

9
00:00:18,630 --> 00:00:20,710
So what do robots mean for Xpeng?

10
00:00:20,710 --> 00:00:23,110
I think, in this world, there are probably many different solutions.

11
00:00:23,110 --> 00:00:26,480
And we chose to go with a humanoid robot, one that is as human-like as possible.

12
00:00:26,480 --> 00:00:27,640
So, what are your odds of success?

13
00:00:27,640 --> 00:00:29,420
We're looking at about a 20% chance.

14
00:00:29,420 --> 00:00:31,900
In an era of such dramatic technological change,

15
00:00:31,900 --> 00:00:32,780
Do you feel anxious?

16
00:00:32,780 --> 00:00:33,620
Of course I'm anxious.

17
00:00:33,620 --> 00:00:36,260
Because you realize that a lot of your old ways of thinking,

18
00:00:36,260 --> 00:00:39,679
Even the foundational theorems and paradigms underlying your entire logical framework...

19
00:00:39,679 --> 00:00:40,719
even down to the level of your axioms.

20
00:00:40,719 --> 00:00:42,359
Your values, your outlook on life, your entire worldview...

21
00:00:42,359 --> 00:00:44,559
With all these things changing, the old ways just don't work anymore.

22
00:00:44,559 --> 00:00:46,460
So, have you made it out of that sea of blood today?

23
00:00:46,460 --> 00:00:47,560
I think everyone is still in the swim.

24
00:00:47,560 --> 00:00:49,020
And I don't think anyone has really made it out yet.

25
00:00:49,020 --> 00:00:50,420
A promise left unfulfilled, a dream that is never-ending.

26
00:00:53,240 --> 00:00:53,720
Hello.

27
00:00:53,720 --> 00:00:54,000
Hello, everyone.

28
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:55,100
and I'm Xiao Jun.

29
00:00:55,100 --> 00:00:56,040
Unfinished Promise is...

30
00:00:56,040 --> 00:00:58,840
a co-production of Weibo Finance and the 'Language is the World' Studio.

31
00:00:58,840 --> 00:01:00,600
a co-produced interview program.

32
00:01:00,600 --> 00:01:05,080
And our guest today is He Xiaopeng, the founder and CEO of XPeng Group.

33
00:01:05,080 --> 00:01:08,780
and let's talk about his explorations in physical AI.

34
00:01:08,780 --> 00:01:12,020
But he's still got a lot of secrets he can't share.

35
00:01:12,020 --> 00:01:13,860
Before we officially kick off the show,

36
00:01:13,860 --> 00:01:17,080
I'd like to start by asking about your personal experience with AI lately.

37
00:01:17,080 --> 00:01:18,400
Let's do a little survey.

38
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:21,360
So, what are the AI products you've been using the most recently?

39
00:01:21,360 --> 00:01:22,680
Well, I don't actually use that many.

40
00:01:22,680 --> 00:01:27,440
I'd say it's still the more traditional AI products like Qwen and Doubao.

41
00:01:27,440 --> 00:01:29,060
But when it comes to coding,

42
00:01:29,060 --> 00:01:32,209
But within our team, we're using it a ton right now.

43
00:01:32,209 --> 00:01:35,029
But personally, I'm not willing to use it myself.

44
00:01:35,029 --> 00:01:36,989
And they asked me why.

45
00:01:36,989 --> 00:01:38,920
Xpeng, you have to use it yourself.

46
00:01:38,920 --> 00:01:42,440
I'll give you a very interesting example.

47
00:01:42,440 --> 00:01:46,130
I said, think back to when we were building internet products.

48
00:01:46,530 --> 00:01:47,890
If you use a product every single day,

49
00:01:47,890 --> 00:01:50,630
you'll quickly get into the nitty-gritty details.

50
00:01:50,630 --> 00:01:54,290
For instance, you might find that certain skills aren't very user-friendly.

51
00:01:54,290 --> 00:01:56,630
If you understand it,

52
00:01:56,630 --> 00:01:58,360
And you start to think,

53
00:01:58,360 --> 00:02:02,120
I believe its advantages have a very long runway ahead.

54
00:02:02,120 --> 00:02:03,240
But once you start diving into it,

55
00:02:03,240 --> 00:02:05,440
you'll start to see its flaws and all the problems it has.

56
00:02:05,440 --> 00:02:08,000
And then all your focus goes into finding a way to solve them.

57
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,650
For instance, issues with multi-person collaboration, coding problems, and a whole host of other related challenges.

58
00:02:11,650 --> 00:02:14,110
Instead, it keeps you from looking further ahead.

59
00:02:14,110 --> 00:02:18,110
So, when it comes to the fast-paced changes in technology and the capabilities of many products...

60
00:02:18,110 --> 00:02:21,660
My personal take is, use it, but don't get too deep into it.

61
00:02:21,660 --> 00:02:23,140
Especially when you're in the top spot.

62
00:02:23,140 --> 00:02:25,650
But for the grassroots level,

63
00:02:25,650 --> 00:02:28,890
Or, let's say, some product lines that are strongly tied to it.

64
00:02:28,890 --> 00:02:32,029
You just have to encourage them, and let them try whatever method they see fit.

65
00:02:32,029 --> 00:02:33,989
In the end, it's all about the results.

66
00:02:33,989 --> 00:02:36,480
And then finally, gradually consolidate it all into one.

67
00:02:36,480 --> 00:02:37,900
That's a better way to do it.

68
00:02:37,900 --> 00:02:40,120
When it comes to AI coding, for the top leader of a company...

69
00:02:40,120 --> 00:02:42,960
Does it even make any sense?

70
00:02:43,190 --> 00:02:45,090
So, what impact do you think this will have on, let's say, XPeng,

71
00:02:45,090 --> 00:02:46,190
or even Xpeng,

72
00:02:46,190 --> 00:02:47,910
or for the entire automotive industry,

73
00:02:47,910 --> 00:02:49,310
or the smart driving industry for that matter,

74
00:02:49,310 --> 00:02:50,630
So what kind of changes will it bring?

75
00:02:50,630 --> 00:02:56,869
I think it's a really great tool for junior programmers.

76
00:02:56,869 --> 00:02:59,269
For now, it's still just an auxiliary tool.

77
00:02:59,269 --> 00:03:01,390
But maybe in two to three years,

78
00:03:01,390 --> 00:03:05,910
It will force entry-level programmers to level up to a senior tier.

79
00:03:05,910 --> 00:03:11,200
But I think for things like assisted driving,

80
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:15,600
or other strong AI capabilities,

81
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:18,240
I think its help becomes much more limited.

82
00:03:18,240 --> 00:03:19,660
It's just one of the tools.

83
00:03:19,660 --> 00:03:21,530
If you truly want to build the entire infrastructure,

84
00:03:21,530 --> 00:03:23,650
to build the whole system up.

85
00:03:23,650 --> 00:03:24,690
Actually, in and of itself,

86
00:03:24,690 --> 00:03:28,760
You can think of it as something that helps everyone at the application layer.

87
00:03:28,760 --> 00:03:29,900
That's AI coding.

88
00:03:29,900 --> 00:03:31,480
But when it comes to the kernel level,

89
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:33,079
For example, let's say you want to write an operating system.

90
00:03:33,079 --> 00:03:36,779
I think the absolute core of it all is the infrastructure.

91
00:03:36,779 --> 00:03:38,040
rather than the coding itself.

92
00:03:38,040 --> 00:03:39,960
So, how many tokens are you guys using on a monthly basis right now?

93
00:03:39,960 --> 00:03:41,910
how many tokens the company will use,

94
00:03:41,910 --> 00:03:44,070
We don't really look at it that way.

95
00:03:44,070 --> 00:03:44,750
Actually, a lot of people are talking about this.

96
00:03:44,750 --> 00:03:48,060
have been talking about this over the past year.

97
00:03:48,060 --> 00:03:50,560
And for small to medium-sized digital companies,

98
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:52,180
and a lot of people bring this up.

99
00:03:52,180 --> 00:03:54,290
I think it's going to be incredibly important.

100
00:03:54,290 --> 00:03:57,630
But for large and medium-sized digital companies, I think you just need to pay them some attention.

101
00:03:57,630 --> 00:03:59,430
They shouldn't go too broad.

102
00:03:59,430 --> 00:04:03,320
Because for some companies, the business supported by digitalization,

103
00:04:03,320 --> 00:04:04,780
might not necessarily be digital.

104
00:04:04,780 --> 00:04:06,340
There might be non-digital ones, uh-huh.

105
00:04:06,340 --> 00:04:07,980
What's really interesting is,

106
00:04:07,980 --> 00:04:11,710
How many tokens does a non-digital company even need?

107
00:04:11,710 --> 00:04:14,490
If you take our cars, for instance,

108
00:04:14,490 --> 00:04:17,210
We actually ran a little interesting stat on that.

109
00:04:17,210 --> 00:04:21,720
With our new generation VLA, if you only use it for three to four hours a day,

110
00:04:21,720 --> 00:04:23,440
how many tokens it would use.

111
00:04:23,440 --> 00:04:25,540
I can't recall the exact number off the top of my head.

112
00:04:25,540 --> 00:04:27,200
Of course, that's just for internal circulation.

113
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:28,500
You can think of it this way,

114
00:04:28,820 --> 00:04:30,300
So, let's look at it from another angle.

115
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:31,580
So, what this means is, for digital AI...

116
00:04:31,580 --> 00:04:36,860
the number of tokens an AI can use

117
00:04:36,860 --> 00:04:41,460
is far, far fewer than the number of tokens an AI would need to operate in the physical world.

118
00:04:41,460 --> 00:04:43,160
But in reality, that's not what matters.

119
00:04:43,160 --> 00:04:46,739
Because it's not about using a person to fulfill its needs, but an AI.

120
00:04:46,739 --> 00:04:47,579
an autonomous car,

121
00:04:47,579 --> 00:04:49,919
You can think of it as an automatic machine.

122
00:04:49,919 --> 00:04:53,650
How many tokens is it using?

123
00:04:53,650 --> 00:04:55,750
So, when it comes to these two fields,

124
00:04:55,750 --> 00:04:58,010
I see them as two different perspectives.

125
00:04:58,010 --> 00:04:59,400
So, in the physical world...

126
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:03,120
In my perspective, the use of tokens in the future will be about machines...

127
00:05:03,120 --> 00:05:04,740
how many Tokens you use yourself,

128
00:05:04,740 --> 00:05:07,960
and how much value is created for both the machine and the human user.

129
00:05:08,600 --> 00:05:12,620
and how many tokens we can use to create value for both people and enterprises.

130
00:05:12,620 --> 00:05:13,800
That's a whole different dimension.

131
00:05:13,800 --> 00:05:15,400
So, its metrics should be different.

132
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:19,159
So, for its North Star Metric, what do you think would be a reasonable number?

133
00:05:19,159 --> 00:05:20,379
I don't know.

134
00:05:20,379 --> 00:05:24,220
Internally, I try my best not to put any controls on tokens for the team.

135
00:05:24,220 --> 00:05:26,220
A lot of people ask why we don't control tokens.

136
00:05:26,220 --> 00:05:28,380
We cut an entire year's worth of expenses in just one quarter.

137
00:05:28,380 --> 00:05:30,400
I think if they can actually pull it off,

138
00:05:30,400 --> 00:05:34,580
And for me, the most crucial part is managing the most abnormal cases.

139
00:05:34,580 --> 00:05:36,400
the top 10 scenarios.

140
00:05:36,400 --> 00:05:38,300
I think everything else can be pretty open.

141
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:42,180
Because you can't be sure that spending a thousand RMB per person, per month is the right move.

142
00:05:42,180 --> 00:05:44,580
or even ten thousand RMB is what's truly valuable.

143
00:05:44,580 --> 00:05:48,549
And take our monthly salaries, for example.

144
00:05:49,099 --> 00:05:50,779
is very likely to far exceed that amount.

145
00:05:50,779 --> 00:05:54,179
If they're truly capable of spending more money to generate even greater value,

146
00:05:54,179 --> 00:05:55,340
So why would you want to restrict that?

147
00:05:55,340 --> 00:05:57,620
So where are the company's main resources being allocated right now?

148
00:05:57,620 --> 00:05:59,660
I think it's mainly GIC.

149
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:02,780
Actually, it was the merger of our autonomous driving and cockpit teams.

150
00:06:02,780 --> 00:06:03,960
And that team is huge.

151
00:06:03,960 --> 00:06:07,859
I think 'token' is a term more for internal use within a company.

152
00:06:07,859 --> 00:06:09,259
In a way,

153
00:06:09,259 --> 00:06:12,039
You can say how many H100s you've used.

154
00:06:12,039 --> 00:06:14,039
I have no idea how many tokens we could use in a single day.

155
00:06:14,039 --> 00:06:16,910
I haven't really figured out that conversion ratio yet.

156
00:06:16,910 --> 00:06:18,090
So, what we're calculating is, for example,

157
00:06:18,090 --> 00:06:21,190
Let's say I give you 30,000 H100s, or even 50,000.

158
00:06:21,190 --> 00:06:26,710
What kind of application can use it with high efficiency and high performance?

159
00:06:26,710 --> 00:06:27,550
So within that,

160
00:06:27,550 --> 00:06:30,420
Let's take a look at the utilization of this computing power.

161
00:06:30,420 --> 00:06:32,640
To be honest, I don't really pay much attention to token usage.

162
00:06:32,640 --> 00:06:35,289
You just mentioned outliers. What kind of outliers are they?

163
00:06:35,289 --> 00:06:36,289
Let me give you an example.

164
00:06:36,289 --> 00:06:39,509
We've recently put a whole new system in place specifically for data control.

165
00:06:39,509 --> 00:06:41,580
Uh...

166
00:06:41,580 --> 00:06:43,860
Everyone talks about the value of data,

167
00:06:43,860 --> 00:06:48,880
I think very few companies are seeing the sheer cost of data right now.

168
00:06:48,880 --> 00:06:52,390
Because in the realm of digital AI, the volume of data is tiny.

169
00:06:52,390 --> 00:06:54,460
You can get by with just a few dozen terabytes for training.

170
00:06:54,460 --> 00:07:00,270
But for us, a single training session can use anywhere from tens to hundreds of terabytes.

171
00:07:00,630 --> 00:07:02,830
So, it all comes down to how you manage the data.

172
00:07:02,830 --> 00:07:06,550
So, the storage costs are a massive expense.

173
00:07:06,550 --> 00:07:08,550
We're probably spending, in a single year,

174
00:07:08,550 --> 00:07:12,990
all in direct, hard costs, amounting to over a billion yuan.

175
00:07:12,990 --> 00:07:16,979
So, the question becomes, what data is actually valuable?

176
00:07:16,979 --> 00:07:19,279
Which data is only temporarily valuable?

177
00:07:19,279 --> 00:07:23,030
Which data needs to be used in real-time?

178
00:07:23,030 --> 00:07:26,470
and which data can be used after a warm-up period.

179
00:07:26,470 --> 00:07:29,840
And the amount of money spent on each one of these is in the tens of millions.

180
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:31,820
And then you can start running the analysis.

181
00:07:31,820 --> 00:07:33,240
And then you can start to optimize.

182
00:07:33,240 --> 00:07:36,020
In fact, there's a huge potential for efficiency gains.

183
00:07:36,020 --> 00:07:39,380
This is the logic behind lowering costs and boosting efficiency.

184
00:07:39,380 --> 00:07:40,760
And it's actually the same for computing power.

185
00:07:40,760 --> 00:07:42,780
We have separate teams for data and for computing power.

186
00:07:42,780 --> 00:07:44,910
to exclusively handle this matter.

187
00:07:44,910 --> 00:07:46,580
But that's not really what we focus on.

188
00:07:46,580 --> 00:07:51,900
I see a lot of companies talking about the number of tokens their engineers use.

189
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:55,750
I think that number, when you compare it to the number of tokens used by the machine,

190
00:07:55,750 --> 00:08:00,139
and the number of tokens required to train a physical-world AI model.

191
00:08:00,139 --> 00:08:01,699
Those are all incredibly small numbers.

192
00:08:01,699 --> 00:08:04,280
Lately, the concept of 'skills' has been getting a lot of buzz.

193
00:08:04,280 --> 00:08:07,300
If we were to train a 'He Xiaopeng Skill'...

194
00:08:07,300 --> 00:08:11,340
So what kind of training data do you think it should be fed?

195
00:08:11,340 --> 00:08:12,880
So, what would that skill be like?

196
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:15,940
I think when it comes to digital models versus physical models,

197
00:08:15,940 --> 00:08:22,090
Right now, it's still relatively easy to codify the skills of entry-level white-collar and blue-collar workers.

198
00:08:22,090 --> 00:08:23,650
are relatively easy to be 'skill-ized'.

199
00:08:23,650 --> 00:08:26,970
If I can already articulate a clear line of logic right now,

200
00:08:26,970 --> 00:08:28,650
So what does this deskilling mean?

201
00:08:28,650 --> 00:08:31,000
It means it's not just the basic blue-collar and white-collar jobs.

202
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:32,740
but even the higher-end white-collar and blue-collar jobs.

203
00:08:32,740 --> 00:08:35,060
This will involve tremendous risks for everyone.

204
00:08:35,060 --> 00:08:36,160
CEOs can be replaced.

205
00:08:36,160 --> 00:08:39,020
Perhaps in a few decades, or maybe a century from now...

206
00:08:39,020 --> 00:08:41,520
By then, my abilities could indeed be replaced by skills.

207
00:08:41,520 --> 00:08:44,850
But by then, perhaps every CEO, including us, will have developed even stronger...

208
00:08:44,850 --> 00:08:46,630
more comprehensive capabilities.

209
00:08:46,630 --> 00:08:48,230
He might have given up on A, B, and C,

210
00:08:48,230 --> 00:08:49,960
but gained new skills DEF in return.

211
00:08:49,960 --> 00:08:52,480
Because that's a question we've not just thought about,

212
00:08:52,480 --> 00:08:54,069
We've deeply considered it.

213
00:08:54,069 --> 00:08:56,289
Because we are currently involved in a lot of robotics work.

214
00:08:56,289 --> 00:08:57,989
Because, actually, if you look at it from another angle...

215
00:08:57,989 --> 00:08:59,149
I think in this space,

216
00:08:59,149 --> 00:09:02,930
In fact, there are two very important contradictions at play here.

217
00:09:02,930 --> 00:09:05,390
I think for most people, they'd be thinking, how do I...

218
00:09:05,390 --> 00:09:08,920
or package his abilities into a set of skills.

219
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:11,160
But from a model's perspective,

220
00:09:11,160 --> 00:09:14,760
So how would I know that your skillification process actually produced the right capability?

221
00:09:14,760 --> 00:09:16,200
and constantly being online.

222
00:09:16,200 --> 00:09:19,759
For instance, within a physical simulation model, you can perform reinforcement learning.

223
00:09:19,759 --> 00:09:20,859
But in reality, with this stuff,

224
00:09:20,859 --> 00:09:24,480
It's completely different from coding, or even from autonomous driving.

225
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:27,120
Coding and autonomous driving, relatively speaking, are quite clear-cut.

226
00:09:27,120 --> 00:09:30,079
I know what's wrong, yeah.

227
00:09:30,079 --> 00:09:33,059
But let's say, for instance, we try to 'skillify' He Xiaopeng himself.

228
00:09:33,059 --> 00:09:36,239
it's very difficult to figure out what the right way to 'He Xiaopeng-ify' it is,

229
00:09:36,239 --> 00:09:37,359
or what's wrong.

230
00:09:37,359 --> 00:09:38,630
It's extremely difficult.

231
00:09:38,630 --> 00:09:40,750
So, within a system like this,

232
00:09:40,750 --> 00:09:42,190
The point is, we're building the framework ourselves.

233
00:09:42,190 --> 00:09:44,870
rather than just using a system that someone else has already built.

234
00:09:44,870 --> 00:09:46,070
From my perspective,

235
00:09:46,070 --> 00:09:48,010
So these are completely two different perspectives, really.

236
00:09:48,010 --> 00:09:48,870
It's a whole drama.

237
00:09:48,870 --> 00:09:52,920
So, intuitively, what would you say is a weakness of He Xiaopeng's skillset? A flaw?

238
00:09:52,920 --> 00:09:55,340
I think once a person's abilities are systematized into 'key skills'...

239
00:09:55,340 --> 00:09:59,030
you'll find that this person actually has a ton of flaws.

240
00:09:59,830 --> 00:10:03,060
What about you? Of course, we all do.

241
00:10:03,060 --> 00:10:04,020
As a CEO,

242
00:10:04,020 --> 00:10:06,260
So, do you think your current AI capabilities are enough?

243
00:10:06,260 --> 00:10:07,180
I don't know.

244
00:10:07,180 --> 00:10:11,380
I think for many companies in the digital world,

245
00:10:11,380 --> 00:10:16,340
I think they could probably dedicate, say, tens of percent of their work to AI.

246
00:10:16,340 --> 00:10:18,380
But I don't think that's the case for the physical world.

247
00:10:18,380 --> 00:10:20,280
XPeng is an enterprise with tens of thousands of employees.

248
00:10:20,280 --> 00:10:23,680
I think spending 15 to 20 percent on AI is appropriate.

249
00:10:23,680 --> 00:10:26,780
And the AI I'm talking about is an umbrella term.

250
00:10:26,780 --> 00:10:30,520
This includes our autonomous driving,

251
00:10:30,520 --> 00:10:32,200
and our robotics.

252
00:10:32,200 --> 00:10:35,020
We consider all of these to fall under the broader umbrella of AI.

253
00:10:35,020 --> 00:10:36,510
I think that's more than enough.

254
00:10:36,510 --> 00:10:38,350
Well, there's a topic I'm very keen to discuss with you today.

255
00:10:38,350 --> 00:10:40,910
So, if you have AI companies on one side,

256
00:10:40,910 --> 00:10:42,530
and a manufacturing company on the other.

257
00:10:42,530 --> 00:10:45,720
So, how do you strike a balance between the two?

258
00:10:45,720 --> 00:10:48,500
Do you find yourself caught in a dilemma, feeling pulled in different directions?

259
00:10:48,500 --> 00:10:51,960
So, are you ultimately choosing to be an AI company, or a traditional manufacturing-based car company?

260
00:10:51,960 --> 00:10:53,420
Actually, I don't see it that way.

261
00:10:53,420 --> 00:10:54,280
I'm sorry.

262
00:10:54,280 --> 00:10:58,220
The way I see it, there are a few different kinds of R&D when it comes to cars.

263
00:10:58,220 --> 00:11:00,810
I think the first one is hardware R&D.

264
00:11:01,270 --> 00:11:02,550
The second is software development.

265
00:11:02,550 --> 00:11:04,650
And AI is just one part of that.

266
00:11:04,650 --> 00:11:05,690
one part of the software.

267
00:11:05,690 --> 00:11:07,850
And I think there's one more: R&D for manufacturing.

268
00:11:07,850 --> 00:11:08,650
Going back to what you were just saying, Xiao Jun...

269
00:11:08,650 --> 00:11:14,450
R&D for hardware and manufacturing are two different capabilities.

270
00:11:14,450 --> 00:11:18,920
For instance, you might have the ability to design a very beautiful table and chair.

271
00:11:18,920 --> 00:11:20,920
But you might not be able to actually build it.

272
00:11:21,960 --> 00:11:24,180
These are two different skill sets.

273
00:11:24,180 --> 00:11:27,260
And this is why, I think, for an automotive company...

274
00:11:27,260 --> 00:11:31,320
In fact, developing these four capabilities is the fundamental foundation.

275
00:11:31,320 --> 00:11:33,160
And in the future, we might even see a fifth one.

276
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:34,250
At least, that's my take on it.

277
00:11:34,250 --> 00:11:37,630
But just last year, you were still calling yourselves an AI car company.

278
00:11:37,630 --> 00:11:39,490
This year, XPeng Motors just completed a rebranding.

279
00:11:39,490 --> 00:11:40,710
saying that Xiaomi Auto is now called XPENG Group.

280
00:11:40,710 --> 00:11:42,660
You're now calling yourselves a 'Physical AI' company.

281
00:11:42,660 --> 00:11:45,500
So what's the reason behind this name change?

282
00:11:45,500 --> 00:11:48,540
From an AI car company to a Physical AI company.

283
00:11:48,540 --> 00:11:49,740
So, what's the change here?

284
00:11:49,740 --> 00:11:52,170
I think this change is just the beginning.

285
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:54,840
And there's still so much that's hard to articulate clearly.

286
00:11:54,840 --> 00:11:56,020
But I can shed some light on it.

287
00:11:56,020 --> 00:11:58,130
For example, let's take XPeng's first ten years,

288
00:11:58,130 --> 00:12:00,530
So, during the first 10 years of this entrepreneurial journey,

289
00:12:00,530 --> 00:12:04,210
In fact, everything we did revolved around three core words, or six characters in Chinese.

290
00:12:04,210 --> 00:12:06,030
or in other words, smart electric vehicles.

291
00:12:06,030 --> 00:12:09,460
So, looking back at the last decade of entrepreneurship,

292
00:12:09,460 --> 00:12:10,960
We built our first car,

293
00:12:10,960 --> 00:12:12,780
and then put it into mass production,

294
00:12:12,780 --> 00:12:14,690
sold our first 100,000 units,

295
00:12:14,690 --> 00:12:16,490
then build a second model, and so on.

296
00:12:16,490 --> 00:12:19,170
And it would just get stuck in that kind of cycle.

297
00:12:19,170 --> 00:12:22,170
But the reality is, 12 years ago...

298
00:12:22,170 --> 00:12:23,690
And that was back in 2014, when XPeng Motors was founded.

299
00:12:23,690 --> 00:12:25,230
Yeah.

300
00:12:25,230 --> 00:12:26,990
hardly anyone believed in the idea of smart technology.

301
00:12:26,990 --> 00:12:29,940
But a small minority did believe in electrification.

302
00:12:29,940 --> 00:12:32,360
More people believed that the auto business was just about the individual car.

303
00:12:32,360 --> 00:12:37,480
So, back in 2025, which was actually last year...

304
00:12:37,480 --> 00:12:39,720
Everyone was convinced that electrification was the future.

305
00:12:39,720 --> 00:12:41,200
Because from China to the rest of the world, what everyone saw...

306
00:12:41,200 --> 00:12:44,260
a shift towards new energy sources.

307
00:12:44,260 --> 00:12:47,580
So, over the past few years,

308
00:12:47,580 --> 00:12:50,380
In reality, even though intelligent technology has been advancing incredibly fast,

309
00:12:50,380 --> 00:12:51,900
In the automotive sector,

310
00:12:51,900 --> 00:12:56,910
But in reality, I think the progress has been far from satisfactory.

311
00:12:56,910 --> 00:13:01,100
Because, even dating back much earlier, there have been many companies...

312
00:13:01,100 --> 00:13:03,920
From Toyota to Google, to China's Baidu,

313
00:13:03,920 --> 00:13:07,300
Overseas, you have automakers like Tesla, and in China, companies such as Xpeng...

314
00:13:07,300 --> 00:13:11,370
We've all been pouring a lot of effort into assisted driving.

315
00:13:11,370 --> 00:13:14,510
In a way, I think it did achieve some results.

316
00:13:14,510 --> 00:13:17,520
But it just didn't have enough sophistication.

317
00:13:17,520 --> 00:13:22,349
In other words, back then, I still believed it was all about the AI algorithms.

318
00:13:22,349 --> 00:13:25,789
combined with the capabilities of software-based rules.

319
00:13:25,789 --> 00:13:28,089
I jokingly call it a 'stitched-together monstrosity'.

320
00:13:28,089 --> 00:13:31,150
In reality, the robot wasn't designed to be fully AI-driven.

321
00:13:31,150 --> 00:13:33,250
nor was it utilizing the full capabilities of the AI model itself.

322
00:13:33,250 --> 00:13:34,790
to build this system.

323
00:13:34,790 --> 00:13:37,270
The logic is still primarily software-based.

324
00:13:37,270 --> 00:13:41,530
At XPeng, we feel that we also encountered a very significant change last year.

325
00:13:41,530 --> 00:13:45,070
So, what that means is, at the time, we were actually working on two different generations in parallel.

326
00:13:45,070 --> 00:13:46,690
the new intelligent assisted driving system.

327
00:13:46,690 --> 00:13:49,110
Internally, we call it the first generation of VLA.

328
00:13:49,110 --> 00:13:51,580
VLA's second generation... and our VLA's first generation.

329
00:13:51,580 --> 00:13:55,540
Essentially, we're taking what we had in the previous end-to-end framework and just scaling it up.

330
00:13:55,540 --> 00:13:56,860
and scaling up the model.

331
00:13:56,860 --> 00:13:59,440
and reduce the reliance on hard-coded rules in the software.

332
00:13:59,440 --> 00:14:03,020
and expanding the scenarios and scope of its application.

333
00:14:03,020 --> 00:14:04,580
This enhances the back-end capabilities.

334
00:14:04,580 --> 00:14:05,740
For instance, reinforcement learning.

335
00:14:05,740 --> 00:14:07,040
like post-training,

336
00:14:07,040 --> 00:14:08,200
So that's one approach.

337
00:14:08,200 --> 00:14:09,500
But actually, another possible direction is to say,

338
00:14:09,500 --> 00:14:14,800
How do I let go of the old, end-to-end logic

339
00:14:14,800 --> 00:14:17,560
Instead, what we're doing is using a much larger foundation model.

340
00:14:17,560 --> 00:14:24,880
is thinking more about how to first push the upper limits of autonomous driving.

341
00:14:24,880 --> 00:14:26,440
and then work on raising the floor.

342
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:30,069
And by 'closing the gap on the lower bound,' what I mean is simply making fewer mistakes.

343
00:14:30,069 --> 00:14:31,489
according to the agreement you've set,

344
00:14:31,489 --> 00:14:33,749
and act in ways that meet your expectations.

345
00:14:33,749 --> 00:14:34,839
and is capable of movement.

346
00:14:34,839 --> 00:14:36,639
But in reality, its generalization capabilities...

347
00:14:36,639 --> 00:14:38,719
and performs poorly in many areas.

348
00:14:38,719 --> 00:14:39,659
For example,

349
00:14:39,659 --> 00:14:45,240
The thing is, as of today, no self-driving company's software

350
00:14:45,240 --> 00:14:48,500
that can drive smoothly in an underground parking garage.

351
00:14:48,500 --> 00:14:51,760
What all these systems offer in parking lots is what's called memory-assisted driving.

352
00:14:51,760 --> 00:14:53,240
In reality, it's only after it's driven the route once...

353
00:14:53,240 --> 00:14:56,300
It knows where your parking spot is,

354
00:14:56,300 --> 00:14:59,300
what your general driving route looks like,

355
00:14:59,300 --> 00:15:01,660
The thing is, its understanding of the entire physical world...

356
00:15:01,660 --> 00:15:02,940
is extremely low.

357
00:15:02,940 --> 00:15:04,550
The core issue is that it's just not smart enough.

358
00:15:04,550 --> 00:15:06,310
Its ceiling is just too low.

359
00:15:06,310 --> 00:15:10,190
So you could say that to achieve something really great, you need to unlock a potential of ten thousand points.

360
00:15:10,190 --> 00:15:12,570
But they were probably all just around the one-thousand-point mark.

361
00:15:12,570 --> 00:15:14,640
This is just a hypothetical.

362
00:15:14,640 --> 00:15:16,600
So, let's look at it from another angle.

363
00:15:16,600 --> 00:15:19,660
It was around this time last year, I'd say.

364
00:15:19,660 --> 00:15:21,600
our next-generation VLA

365
00:15:21,600 --> 00:15:23,760
I feel like it opened a whole new door for me.

366
00:15:23,760 --> 00:15:27,680
I think its potential could be from, say, a hundred thousand points all the way up to a million.

367
00:15:27,680 --> 00:15:30,370
But back then, the downside was also brutal.

368
00:15:30,370 --> 00:15:31,710
Originally, you'd expect to build a product,

369
00:15:31,710 --> 00:15:33,590
and a floor score of 900.

370
00:15:33,590 --> 00:15:35,510
At this point, you're pretty capable.

371
00:15:35,510 --> 00:15:37,710
But back then, the baseline might have only been 100 points.

372
00:15:37,710 --> 00:15:39,090
So, compared to others,

373
00:15:39,090 --> 00:15:42,090
the baseline for our own products had to be set even lower.

374
00:15:42,090 --> 00:15:45,159
Plus, its engineering side was plagued with tons of problems.

375
00:15:45,159 --> 00:15:48,399
But in the end, we made a huge bet.

376
00:15:48,399 --> 00:15:52,950
So, let's just say, in the past, we used a software-engineering approach.

377
00:15:52,950 --> 00:15:58,530
We took the software process and叠加了 (stacked on) the algorithms and tools of AI.

378
00:15:58,530 --> 00:16:01,750
Including what you just mentioned about coding.

379
00:16:01,750 --> 00:16:06,470
You could think of it as being part of a business workflow, but it's still within the realm of software.

380
00:16:06,470 --> 00:16:14,950
In certain key parts of the tools and processes, we do use AI.

381
00:16:15,850 --> 00:16:17,530
But we believed that was the wrong approach.

382
00:16:17,530 --> 00:16:19,170
So, this is still just stitching things together, isn't it?

383
00:16:19,170 --> 00:16:24,655
The output is still just software.

384
00:16:25,070 --> 00:16:27,650
Because you're still using a software methodology.

385
00:16:27,650 --> 00:16:33,730
You're using AI as a toolbox to create more powerful software.

386
00:16:33,730 --> 00:16:36,230
I'd call it an 'AI Frankenstein's monster'.

387
00:16:36,230 --> 00:16:43,630
Last year, we made a massive transformation, which was also a huge gamble.

388
00:16:44,710 --> 00:16:49,200
We just shut down our entire old system.

389
00:16:49,200 --> 00:16:52,260
And that system cost us a good few billion.

390
00:16:52,260 --> 00:16:53,600
And when was this, last year?

391
00:16:53,600 --> 00:16:55,900
Around this time, last year. And the reason?

392
00:16:55,900 --> 00:16:58,280
I don't think it can achieve true autonomous driving.

393
00:16:58,280 --> 00:17:01,520
And I don't think it's possible to allow for the true generalization of robots either.

394
00:17:01,520 --> 00:17:04,950
For instance, let's say we walk into a venue we've never been to before.

395
00:17:04,950 --> 00:17:06,350
The robot can walk over and say, "Hello, Jun."

396
00:17:06,350 --> 00:17:07,450
and then sit down.

397
00:17:07,450 --> 00:17:10,610
And then you might say, "You know what? I'm not going to offer you a glass of water."

398
00:17:10,610 --> 00:17:12,470
And it would say, "Yeah, I don't need it."

399
00:17:12,470 --> 00:17:17,600
I think it's probably a system of strong rules, combined with a few algorithms.

400
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:20,120
utilizing one of the AI's capabilities.

401
00:17:20,120 --> 00:17:20,740
So at that moment, we made a judgment call for ourselves...

402
00:17:20,740 --> 00:17:24,619
The thing is, with smart electric vehicles...

403
00:17:24,619 --> 00:17:28,990
What we were aiming for was a car that's incredibly intelligent.

404
00:17:28,990 --> 00:17:34,180
But the method we were using meant it would never be infinitely smart.

405
00:17:34,180 --> 00:17:35,820
So why did it take until last year to realize this?

406
00:17:35,820 --> 00:17:38,740
So, XPeng has been around for 11 years, right?

407
00:17:38,740 --> 00:17:40,340
And you guys got into intelligent systems pretty early on, too.

408
00:17:40,340 --> 00:17:44,150
I think the vast majority of them are not approaching it from the perspective of physical AI.

409
00:17:44,150 --> 00:17:46,110
to look at something.

410
00:17:46,110 --> 00:17:50,130
I think Physical AI is going to change a lot of things.

411
00:17:50,130 --> 00:17:54,420
They are two completely different things.

412
00:17:54,420 --> 00:17:56,660
Different methodologies, different paths.

413
00:17:56,660 --> 00:18:00,920
But the vast majority of people still view digital AI from a purely research-oriented perspective.

414
00:18:00,920 --> 00:18:04,600
In a way, digital AI is actually based on human language.

415
00:18:04,600 --> 00:18:06,900
Physical AI, on the other hand, doesn't use human language.

416
00:18:06,900 --> 00:18:09,450
Digital AI is human language.

417
00:18:09,450 --> 00:18:12,860
it's highly generalized and condensed.

418
00:18:12,860 --> 00:18:14,460
Exactly. That's why language is the world.

419
00:18:14,460 --> 00:18:16,400
But in the physical world...

420
00:18:16,400 --> 00:18:19,699
Just think about the sheer volume of data each one of us is exposed to every single day.

421
00:18:19,699 --> 00:18:25,880
is just way too vast to be summarized, described, restored, or replicated with language.

422
00:18:25,880 --> 00:18:27,220
Let's look at it from another angle.

423
00:18:27,220 --> 00:18:31,280
I once met a CEO in the auto industry

424
00:18:31,280 --> 00:18:34,410
AI in the digital world is easy to use.

425
00:18:34,410 --> 00:18:37,990
After learning about it, you'd think, 'Okay, I think I get the logic behind it.'

426
00:18:37,990 --> 00:18:43,110
and just apply it, scale it, and use it.

427
00:18:43,110 --> 00:18:46,690
But back then, not a single CEO would say, "I'm going all in on this."

428
00:18:46,690 --> 00:18:50,010
Because I just don't know how truly effective it is.

429
00:18:50,010 --> 00:18:53,950
Because you have to understand, in the digital AI market...

430
00:18:53,950 --> 00:18:56,430
For a lot of models, it's all just about running benchmarks and comparing scores.

431
00:18:56,430 --> 00:18:58,570
But in the world of physical AI, I think that's just ridiculous.

432
00:18:58,570 --> 00:19:01,030
Because it's not just about competing on the upper limit,

433
00:19:01,030 --> 00:19:02,110
Like, for example, just running a benchmark score.

434
00:19:02,110 --> 00:19:04,030
It also has to compete on the lower end.

435
00:19:04,030 --> 00:19:05,050
It has to guarantee the baseline performance.

436
00:19:05,050 --> 00:19:06,430
And it also has to compete on breadth.

437
00:19:06,430 --> 00:19:07,690
For example, your quality.

438
00:19:07,690 --> 00:19:11,210
your costs, your materials, your attention to detail,

439
00:19:11,210 --> 00:19:13,750
the extent of what regulations will allow.

440
00:19:13,750 --> 00:19:15,770
All of these are what we call the 'weak links' in the chain.

441
00:19:15,770 --> 00:19:17,960
Strengths and weaknesses.

442
00:19:17,960 --> 00:19:19,200
and narrows need to be broadened.

443
00:19:19,200 --> 00:19:20,340
And the weak spots need to be strengthened.

444
00:19:20,340 --> 00:19:21,780
And the long board needs to be made even longer.

445
00:19:21,780 --> 00:19:23,300
So, in the digital world,

446
00:19:23,300 --> 00:19:25,179
The key is to focus on the long board.

447
00:19:25,179 --> 00:19:27,310
and they don't pay much attention to the other two.

448
00:19:27,310 --> 00:19:30,630
So, in the physical world, a CEO either doesn't dare to make the bet...

449
00:19:30,630 --> 00:19:32,350
Or they might think, 'I've still got so many other planks in my barrel.'

450
00:19:32,350 --> 00:19:33,170
What was I supposed to do?

451
00:19:33,170 --> 00:19:36,390
I guess I'm probably just bolder than most.

452
00:19:36,390 --> 00:19:39,610
Back then, I wasn't sure if it could solve our weak spots either.

453
00:19:39,610 --> 00:19:41,970
Can it turn my biggest weakness into a strength?

454
00:19:41,970 --> 00:19:43,970
We made a huge bet.

455
00:19:43,970 --> 00:19:47,670
So, we believed, and I believe, in Physical AI.

456
00:19:47,670 --> 00:19:49,090
to think differently.

457
00:19:49,090 --> 00:19:50,980
and a different process.

458
00:19:50,980 --> 00:19:53,460
The fundamental structure of the organization itself needs a complete overhaul.

459
00:19:53,460 --> 00:19:56,550
that's how we might be able to do something truly different.

460
00:19:56,550 --> 00:19:58,190
So, the path we're on...

461
00:19:58,190 --> 00:20:00,930
is completely different from the path taken by many of the large model companies we see today,

462
00:20:00,930 --> 00:20:03,940
or companies that build applications on top of models.

463
00:20:03,940 --> 00:20:06,300
we are on a completely different path.

464
00:20:06,300 --> 00:20:07,180
And that's why...

465
00:20:07,180 --> 00:20:09,520
I see these 'token' companies as all being application-focused.

466
00:20:09,520 --> 00:20:13,580
What they care about, we've actually been on a completely different plane for a long time now.

467
00:20:13,580 --> 00:20:15,860
Because, back when I was working on smart electric vehicles...

468
00:20:15,860 --> 00:20:17,380
But there was always one thing I found particularly painful.

469
00:20:17,380 --> 00:20:19,180
I mean, no matter how you look at it,

470
00:20:19,180 --> 00:20:22,939
the proportion of what a customer needs that is hardware,

471
00:20:22,939 --> 00:20:24,819
is far greater than 50%.

472
00:20:24,819 --> 00:20:28,780
Right. And I believe that in the coming decade,

473
00:20:28,780 --> 00:20:29,740
most likely,

474
00:20:29,740 --> 00:20:34,470
Hardware and software could each take up 50% of that.

475
00:20:34,790 --> 00:20:40,350
So, you have to use AI to fundamentally reboot your entire organization.

476
00:20:40,350 --> 00:20:44,650
design the integration of your hardware and software,

477
00:20:44,650 --> 00:20:49,000
and in turn, unlock greater value from AI.

478
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:50,060
Only then, perhaps in the next decade,

479
00:20:50,060 --> 00:20:51,740
possibly within this new decade,

480
00:20:51,740 --> 00:20:55,840
the comprehensive value of a software's performance and capabilities—the value users are actually willing to pay for.

481
00:20:55,840 --> 00:20:58,710
will account for, say, a car...

482
00:20:58,710 --> 00:21:02,750
or even 50% of a robot's value.

483
00:21:02,750 --> 00:21:04,970
I think that's a very significant shift.

484
00:21:04,970 --> 00:21:08,150
And that's why at XPeng, we've started to rethink our approach.

485
00:21:08,150 --> 00:21:11,570
on how to integrate physical... and 'physical' includes cars,

486
00:21:11,570 --> 00:21:17,130
And this isn't just limited to cars, but to what can be deeply integrated with AI.

487
00:21:17,130 --> 00:21:18,740
Our AI, in fact, deals with digital AI...

488
00:21:18,740 --> 00:21:23,370
I think they're all basically just for using.

489
00:21:23,370 --> 00:21:25,470
Take Claude Code for example, it's fantastic.

490
00:21:25,470 --> 00:21:27,030
I... I would use Claude Code.

491
00:21:27,030 --> 00:21:31,670
If DeepSeek V4 is also really good in certain areas,

492
00:21:31,670 --> 00:21:33,070
And the cost is also fantastic.

493
00:21:33,070 --> 00:21:35,550
then I would switch that portion of our work over to it.

494
00:21:35,550 --> 00:21:37,190
We built a Hub.

495
00:21:37,190 --> 00:21:38,470
The switch can be made very easily.

496
00:21:38,470 --> 00:21:39,590
But with Physical AI,

497
00:21:39,590 --> 00:21:42,320
the models are different,

498
00:21:42,320 --> 00:21:44,600
The data for physical AI is different.

499
00:21:44,600 --> 00:21:47,400
The infrastructure for Physical AI is different.

500
00:21:47,400 --> 00:21:49,500
So, the final effect it produces...

501
00:21:49,500 --> 00:21:53,140
If we can successfully connect all three of those building blocks I just mentioned,

502
00:21:53,140 --> 00:21:55,490
then we might be able to create something truly different.

503
00:21:55,490 --> 00:21:58,990
So, that's the general framework of what we can talk about.

504
00:21:58,990 --> 00:22:00,710
But I think that's all I can say for now.

505
00:22:00,710 --> 00:22:02,330
So, what exactly happened last April?

506
00:22:02,330 --> 00:22:04,730
So why make such a massive bet last April?

507
00:22:04,730 --> 00:22:05,930
Did something trigger it?

508
00:22:05,930 --> 00:22:07,090
Oh, no. Not really.

509
00:22:07,090 --> 00:22:09,830
It was really about experiencing different capabilities.

510
00:22:09,830 --> 00:22:12,599
Last March, I was thinking...

511
00:22:12,599 --> 00:22:14,719
Why does every company seem to think that...

512
00:22:14,719 --> 00:22:18,059
using a simpler methodology and achieving faster results,

513
00:22:18,059 --> 00:22:23,180
you can just whip up a seemingly good-enough autonomous driving system.

514
00:22:23,180 --> 00:22:24,480
And they're not wrong.

515
00:22:24,480 --> 00:22:26,920
But after working on it for a year or two,

516
00:22:26,920 --> 00:22:30,290
you start to realize that to solve for so many of its shortcomings,

517
00:22:30,290 --> 00:22:32,470
it was actually limiting its own strengths.

518
00:22:32,470 --> 00:22:36,389
So, it realized it could never reach Level 4 or Level 5.

519
00:22:36,389 --> 00:22:39,029
So, that was an idea we had back at the beginning of last year.

520
00:22:39,029 --> 00:22:42,149
Maybe this path was just a shortcut.

521
00:22:42,149 --> 00:22:43,800
But it wasn't the main road.

522
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:44,800
It's a small path.

523
00:22:44,800 --> 00:22:46,320
We need to find a major thoroughfare.

524
00:22:46,320 --> 00:22:47,580
To actually make it happen,

525
00:22:47,580 --> 00:22:51,540
Perhaps, about that 50-50 value split between hardware and software I just mentioned.

526
00:22:51,540 --> 00:22:54,100
And when I talk about 'value,' I'm not talking about how the tech guys think about it.

527
00:22:54,100 --> 00:22:56,690
It's the value that customers are willing to pay for.

528
00:22:56,690 --> 00:22:59,170
A user is willing to say, 'I'll buy a 300,000 RMB car.'

529
00:22:59,170 --> 00:23:00,890
Let's say 150k of that is for your hardware.

530
00:23:00,890 --> 00:23:03,210
and the other 150,000 is for the comprehensive capabilities of your software.

531
00:23:03,210 --> 00:23:04,010
So, does a car like that even exist?

532
00:23:04,010 --> 00:23:04,960
Not right now.

533
00:23:04,960 --> 00:23:07,500
But I'm certain that will change within this decade.

534
00:23:07,500 --> 00:23:11,180
So, you have changes in the physical world and changes in AI.

535
00:23:11,180 --> 00:23:12,200
We've had to completely rethink everything.

536
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:15,870
I think this is a very crucial point.

537
00:23:15,870 --> 00:23:18,630
So, as we look ahead to this new decade for XPeng,

538
00:23:18,630 --> 00:23:19,470
And what everyone will see is,

539
00:23:19,470 --> 00:23:22,610
I think we'll probably still talk about smart electric vehicles,

540
00:23:22,610 --> 00:23:23,770
and it will remain our core focus.

541
00:23:23,770 --> 00:23:26,380
But we're no longer just thinking in terms of electric...

542
00:23:26,380 --> 00:23:27,840
or the traditional automotive way to think about intelligence.

543
00:23:27,840 --> 00:23:29,340
Instead, we've shifted our entire logic.

544
00:23:29,340 --> 00:23:33,569
And for everything we consider as a company, starting from the planning phase,

545
00:23:33,569 --> 00:23:37,189
Or rather, from strategic planning all the way to the R&D process.

546
00:23:37,189 --> 00:23:39,010
everything would be gradually adjusted.

547
00:23:39,010 --> 00:23:41,530
Was there a specific, pivotal meeting around March or April of last year?

548
00:23:41,530 --> 00:23:42,520
Within the company,

549
00:23:42,520 --> 00:23:44,340
So you made this huge gamble.

550
00:23:44,340 --> 00:23:48,840
So, the first half of last year was when XPeng's sales were starting to pick up, right?

551
00:23:48,840 --> 00:23:52,329
And then I started thinking more about the direction for the next decade.

552
00:23:52,329 --> 00:23:54,989
I think it wasn't a matter of a single meeting. It was basically a snap decision that just clicked in my head.

553
00:23:54,989 --> 00:23:55,909
to go all in.

554
00:23:55,909 --> 00:23:58,670
I think it was around the end of the third quarter last year.

555
00:23:58,670 --> 00:24:02,020
At the end of the third quarter, we made a huge move.

556
00:24:02,020 --> 00:24:04,200
We took our entire autonomous driving center...

557
00:24:04,200 --> 00:24:06,060
We completely restructured the core organization.

558
00:24:06,060 --> 00:24:11,360
In every given period of time, there are always a great number of brilliant minds out there.

559
00:24:11,360 --> 00:24:15,320
But everyone has their own惯性, their own ingrained ways of doing things.

560
00:24:15,320 --> 00:24:17,560
You get used to doing things the old way.

561
00:24:17,560 --> 00:24:22,020
You should leverage the latest tools and technologies to build something better.

562
00:24:22,020 --> 00:24:24,320
And I think that's the right approach, most of the time.

563
00:24:24,320 --> 00:24:26,920
But there are also many times when you have to completely change your methodology.

564
00:24:28,240 --> 00:24:32,350
So I believe it's about adjusting your methodology, your mindset.

565
00:24:32,350 --> 00:24:35,190
So it sounds like that was a decision you made in your head.

566
00:24:35,190 --> 00:24:38,250
Internally, there probably wasn't one single,标志性 meeting to mark it.

567
00:24:38,250 --> 00:24:40,310
or a specific turning point.

568
00:24:40,310 --> 00:24:42,950
But once you'd made that decision,

569
00:24:42,950 --> 00:24:44,230
So, what did you do right after that?

570
00:24:44,230 --> 00:24:46,760
So, this is what you call an 'AI-driven organization'

571
00:24:46,760 --> 00:24:48,400
Using AI for design.

572
00:24:48,400 --> 00:24:49,540
integrated software and hardware.

573
00:24:49,540 --> 00:24:50,580
So, what's next?

574
00:24:50,580 --> 00:24:52,500
So, for an organization of this scale,

575
00:24:52,500 --> 00:24:55,100
Could you share your steps with us?

576
00:24:55,100 --> 00:24:56,820
So I can't really apologize for any of this, sorry.

577
00:24:56,820 --> 00:24:59,870
So these are the things we're working on.

578
00:24:59,870 --> 00:25:01,770
Of course, it's something we're tackling in stages.

579
00:25:01,770 --> 00:25:03,830
All I can say is,

580
00:25:03,830 --> 00:25:06,140
Different businesses require different pacing.

581
00:25:06,140 --> 00:25:10,160
For the same business unit, the core issue is always about the leadership and the organization.

582
00:25:10,160 --> 00:25:11,920
In reality, it's an incredibly difficult task.

583
00:25:11,920 --> 00:25:14,180
So, why the insistence on an AI-driven approach?

584
00:25:14,180 --> 00:25:16,340
So, what happens when you stick with the old way of thinking?

585
00:25:16,340 --> 00:25:19,800
Well, you're just working within the logic of the software.

586
00:25:19,800 --> 00:25:21,780
because you're just creating a more complex monstrosity.

587
00:25:21,780 --> 00:25:23,440
It's like trying to renovate a house.

588
00:25:23,440 --> 00:25:26,560
You'll be using more materials, more techniques, and leveraging AI.

589
00:25:26,560 --> 00:25:30,440
But the methodology is still about fixing an old house.

590
00:25:30,440 --> 00:25:32,949
What you end up with is still the same old house.

591
00:25:32,949 --> 00:25:34,649
It's just that the repairs might be a bit faster.

592
00:25:34,649 --> 00:25:36,429
But we're looking for something different.

593
00:25:36,429 --> 00:25:37,469
When it comes to the very foundation of something truly different,

594
00:25:37,469 --> 00:25:40,729
At the most fundamental stage, people need to see results.

595
00:25:40,729 --> 00:25:42,250
That's how you earn their belief.

596
00:25:42,250 --> 00:25:43,930
But as the CEO of a company,

597
00:25:43,930 --> 00:25:48,230
I think so. Sometimes, you have to have faith in the milestones along the way.

598
00:25:48,230 --> 00:25:49,270
You have to show everyone what you're doing.

599
00:25:49,270 --> 00:25:50,860
Because it can boost everyone's confidence.

600
00:25:50,860 --> 00:25:52,420
and boost leadership.

601
00:25:52,420 --> 00:25:54,900
A lot of the time, it's about making strategic moves because you have the belief in them.

602
00:25:54,900 --> 00:25:56,460
But for a small company like ours,

603
00:25:56,460 --> 00:25:58,420
it's a whole different ball game compared to a large corporation.

604
00:25:58,420 --> 00:26:00,100
Despite XPeng being a startup,

605
00:26:00,100 --> 00:26:01,540
But in terms of scale,

606
00:26:01,540 --> 00:26:04,949
in terms of headcount, it's already quite large, with tens of thousands of employees.

607
00:26:04,949 --> 00:26:07,870
So, how do you manage such a large group of people and keep them on track?

608
00:26:07,870 --> 00:26:09,850
I think it's a completely different ball game.

609
00:26:09,850 --> 00:26:10,850
that kind of behavior.

610
00:26:10,850 --> 00:26:14,570
So, it's really difficult for me to share insights on the planning and organization of our physical AI endeavors at this point.

611
00:26:14,570 --> 00:26:17,130
So that's why, just now, when you asked me that question...

612
00:26:17,130 --> 00:26:18,550
I've already told you it's a question I can't answer.

613
00:26:18,550 --> 00:26:20,889
First, we're still in the testing phase, running trials.

614
00:26:20,889 --> 00:26:24,729
And second, we don't share any of our plans or goals externally.

615
00:26:24,729 --> 00:26:26,689
So, why are there some things you just don't talk about?

616
00:26:26,689 --> 00:26:30,210
Because it's very difficult to find someone who can accurately discuss it with you.

617
00:26:30,210 --> 00:26:33,370
You can only listen to the thoughts and opinions of many different people.

618
00:26:33,370 --> 00:26:35,210
but most of them are probably wrong.

619
00:26:35,210 --> 00:26:38,520
Because none of them are giving you advice from a big-picture perspective.

620
00:26:38,520 --> 00:26:40,020
They're all just looking from a certain angle.

621
00:26:40,020 --> 00:26:42,040
But the big picture, that's on you.

622
00:26:42,040 --> 00:26:45,340
These different angles come from various friends and your own line of reasoning.

623
00:26:45,340 --> 00:26:46,520
You have to bring it all together.

624
00:26:46,520 --> 00:26:47,660
And in the end, you're the one who places the bet.

625
00:26:47,660 --> 00:26:48,780
It's a lot like starting a business.

626
00:26:48,780 --> 00:26:51,740
I've heard you've become more of a risk-taker over the past three years. Is that right?

627
00:26:51,740 --> 00:26:53,080
Not really.

628
00:26:53,080 --> 00:26:57,520
I think it's just that, a lot of the time,

629
00:26:57,800 --> 00:27:00,240
you know, when you have to place a bet,

630
00:27:00,240 --> 00:27:02,110
the sooner you do, the better.

631
00:27:02,110 --> 00:27:03,910
It's not that I've become a bigger risk-taker.

632
00:27:03,910 --> 00:27:05,330
It was around the end of 2022.

633
00:27:05,330 --> 00:27:07,550
Back when XPeng was facing a lot of challenges,

634
00:27:07,550 --> 00:27:10,489
So, I came up with two ideas at that time.

635
00:27:10,489 --> 00:27:11,829
So they are both related to taking a gamble.

636
00:27:11,829 --> 00:27:13,830
The first is to never admit defeat.

637
00:27:13,830 --> 00:27:15,290
Right.

638
00:27:15,290 --> 00:27:17,130
The second is being willing to face the consequences of a loss.

639
00:27:17,470 --> 00:27:17,750
So...

640
00:27:17,750 --> 00:27:18,190
In fact...

641
00:27:18,190 --> 00:27:21,490
If you can manage to bring these two things together effectively,

642
00:27:21,490 --> 00:27:22,490
and strike a balance,

643
00:27:22,490 --> 00:27:26,010
This means that even when facing immense difficulties,

644
00:27:26,010 --> 00:27:27,050
you have to keep going.

645
00:27:27,050 --> 00:27:28,170
Maybe with just one more push, you'll get through it.

646
00:27:28,170 --> 00:27:29,720
and it just might make it, uh...

647
00:27:29,720 --> 00:27:31,900
But you have to have the right mindset to pull through.

648
00:27:31,900 --> 00:27:33,200
Like I was just saying,

649
00:27:33,200 --> 00:27:37,030
So when it came to the second-generation VLA, I believed we had to go all in on it.

650
00:27:37,030 --> 00:27:41,580
And in the end, we made the firm decision to completely stop the first generation of VLA.

651
00:27:41,580 --> 00:27:44,520
From the business side to the tech side...

652
00:27:44,520 --> 00:27:46,040
all the way down to the organizational level.

653
00:27:46,040 --> 00:27:47,660
So it was a massive...

654
00:27:50,920 --> 00:27:55,370
In a moment like this, the more you hesitate, the longer you wait...

655
00:27:55,370 --> 00:27:56,950
The more you want to wait and see,

656
00:27:56,950 --> 00:27:57,990
And the more you think, 'Let's just wait another six months,' the harder it's going to be to succeed.

657
00:27:57,990 --> 00:28:00,700
Ah,

658
00:28:00,700 --> 00:28:03,260
So, the judgment call you have to make here, in terms of measurement...

659
00:28:03,260 --> 00:28:05,250
That's a really fascinating point.

660
00:28:05,710 --> 00:28:07,050
But I believe that in a few years,

661
00:28:07,050 --> 00:28:08,370
Perhaps we'll talk about it again when we've achieved even greater success.

662
00:28:08,370 --> 00:28:09,270
Maybe we'll talk about it then.

663
00:28:09,270 --> 00:28:11,120
I think, as we go through this process today...

664
00:28:11,120 --> 00:28:13,780
First of all, every company must forge its own path.

665
00:28:19,659 --> 00:28:21,499
Looking at our scale today,

666
00:28:21,499 --> 00:28:24,900
You have to analyze and think critically.

667
00:28:24,900 --> 00:28:28,580
Finding a path that's right for you is what matters most.

668
00:28:28,580 --> 00:28:31,450
And second, everything that's been done in digital AI...

669
00:28:31,450 --> 00:28:34,190
a lot of it can't be replicated in physical AI.

670
00:28:34,190 --> 00:28:36,170
It's a whole different world.

671
00:28:36,170 --> 00:28:39,220
A lot of people talk about embodied AI,

672
00:28:39,220 --> 00:28:40,660
I was even laughing about it back then.

673
00:28:40,660 --> 00:28:44,860
I said, 'First of all, have you ever actually run a business in the physical world?'

674
00:28:45,140 --> 00:28:48,300
If you haven't even successfully built a business in the physical world,

675
00:28:48,300 --> 00:28:50,260
to just coming from a digital world,

676
00:28:50,260 --> 00:28:53,950
to analyze the definitions and laws of the physical world.

677
00:28:53,950 --> 00:28:56,070
to build an AI for the physical world.

678
00:28:56,070 --> 00:28:58,690
I think that's still a narrow definition of the physical world.

679
00:28:58,690 --> 00:29:02,480
But this physical world also involves many, many things that are related to people.

680
00:29:02,480 --> 00:29:06,550
The environment of this physical world, its regulations...

681
00:29:06,550 --> 00:29:08,090
And finally, there's the business side of things.

682
00:29:08,090 --> 00:29:09,670
It's all one cohesive issue.

683
00:29:09,670 --> 00:29:11,159
What can be prioritized,

684
00:29:11,159 --> 00:29:12,399
and what should come later.

685
00:29:12,399 --> 00:29:14,559
Of course, from a pure research perspective, you can ignore all of that.

686
00:29:14,559 --> 00:29:16,159
But if you're looking at it from an engineering perspective,

687
00:29:16,159 --> 00:29:17,819
and then to the scale of mass production.

688
00:29:17,819 --> 00:29:19,280
and then again to the commercial product stage,

689
00:29:19,280 --> 00:29:21,480
and finally, to the perspective of a mass-market product.

690
00:29:21,480 --> 00:29:24,320
you have to think broader and deeper.

691
00:29:24,320 --> 00:29:27,480
rather than just the logic of having two or three strengths.

692
00:29:27,480 --> 00:29:32,029
And that's why I can't give you a simple answer.

693
00:29:32,029 --> 00:29:35,649
I think, you can go and ask any CEO from a digital AI company in the past.

694
00:29:35,649 --> 00:29:36,340
CEO.

695
00:29:36,340 --> 00:29:37,780
None of them will tell you.

696
00:29:37,780 --> 00:29:40,100
the thought process behind their own transformation in AI.

697
00:29:41,260 --> 00:29:43,189
Because you never know if it's going to work out.

698
00:29:43,189 --> 00:29:45,310
And second, they won't share it with you.

699
00:29:45,310 --> 00:29:49,750
But that's a common challenge everyone is facing today, right?

700
00:29:49,750 --> 00:29:52,120
The bottom line is, we absolutely had to transform.

701
00:29:52,120 --> 00:29:55,100
I don't entirely agree with that statement.

702
00:29:55,100 --> 00:29:58,380
So where can digital AI lead to a successful transformation today?

703
00:29:58,380 --> 00:30:01,920
And for which ones it's not necessary. For a large corporation,

704
00:30:01,920 --> 00:30:08,779
For a company with 10,000 or 50,000 employees, delaying the transition by just three days could increase the probability of success by 15%.

705
00:30:08,779 --> 00:30:10,339
But for a micro-company,

706
00:30:10,339 --> 00:30:14,010
If he uses a homogenized methodology and a homogenized organization today,

707
00:30:14,010 --> 00:30:15,250
it won't change a thing.

708
00:30:15,250 --> 00:30:17,080
It can take a gamble.

709
00:30:17,080 --> 00:30:18,160
Because it's small.

710
00:30:18,160 --> 00:30:24,520
And the ways that today's AI can help us basically fall into three categories.

711
00:30:24,520 --> 00:30:27,400
The first one, I think, is the simple analyst.

712
00:30:28,590 --> 00:30:31,270
In fact, there are many areas where I don't even use analysts anymore.

713
00:30:31,270 --> 00:30:32,390
AI is helping me analyze things.

714
00:30:32,390 --> 00:30:34,190
The second is the simple programmer.

715
00:30:34,190 --> 00:30:36,840
And third, a simple designer.

716
00:30:37,080 --> 00:30:39,280
In reality, it's still primarily playing a supporting role.

717
00:30:39,280 --> 00:30:41,610
It has improved efficiency,

718
00:30:41,610 --> 00:30:43,550
It didn't replace anything.

719
00:30:43,550 --> 00:30:46,990
And it doesn't have any mega-scale synergistic effects either.

720
00:30:46,990 --> 00:30:48,530
It hasn't even come close to reaching that point.

721
00:30:48,530 --> 00:30:49,710
So, let's look at it from another angle.

722
00:30:49,710 --> 00:30:53,290
As for the small and micro companies in these three sectors,

723
00:30:53,290 --> 00:30:54,929
I think it's a much better fit.

724
00:30:54,929 --> 00:30:56,449
The pace should be even faster.

725
00:30:56,449 --> 00:30:59,750
But for those not related to these three directions,

726
00:30:59,750 --> 00:31:02,270
Maybe a little later on.

727
00:31:02,270 --> 00:31:03,690
And as for Physical AI,

728
00:31:03,690 --> 00:31:05,590
But the truth is, nobody's really figured it out clearly yet.

729
00:31:05,590 --> 00:31:08,410
So, what jobs exist in the world of physical AI?

730
00:31:08,410 --> 00:31:11,670
So, I just mentioned three types of roles. Which ones are the easiest to get into?

731
00:31:11,670 --> 00:31:14,880
and where we should prioritize implementing them.

732
00:31:14,880 --> 00:31:18,360
From what I've seen, most discussions are about how this will disrupt the world.

733
00:31:18,360 --> 00:31:19,920
is to use AI to improve efficiency.

734
00:31:19,920 --> 00:31:21,520
They have no idea at all.

735
00:31:21,520 --> 00:31:25,160
So, from my perspective, I think there's some truth to that, from certain angles.

736
00:31:25,160 --> 00:31:28,100
But from certain perspectives, it makes absolutely no sense.

737
00:31:28,100 --> 00:31:31,379
We actually believe that in the physical world, a lot of job roles are going to change.

738
00:31:31,379 --> 00:31:33,439
far more than in the digital world.

739
00:31:33,439 --> 00:31:35,339
Because in this world,

740
00:31:35,339 --> 00:31:40,280
If we used to talk about 360 different professions, well now, there are probably 36,000 different jobs.

741
00:31:40,280 --> 00:31:43,780
We believe that in the digital world, the number of jobs is, relatively speaking, quite limited.

742
00:31:43,780 --> 00:31:46,060
Now, a lot of people might see it differently.

743
00:31:46,060 --> 00:31:49,440
A lot of people say, aren't there more white-collar jobs than blue-collar ones?

744
00:31:49,720 --> 00:31:51,100
and there are tons of white-collar jobs.

745
00:31:51,100 --> 00:31:54,580
and they are also positions that blend the digital and physical worlds.

746
00:31:54,580 --> 00:31:58,810
In a way, that's actually true.

747
00:31:58,810 --> 00:32:02,570
I think if we look at the physical world today, let's just say for a start,

748
00:32:02,570 --> 00:32:08,020
Google placed its bet on autonomous driving back in 2009.

749
00:32:08,020 --> 00:32:09,900
And now, 17 years later,

750
00:32:09,900 --> 00:32:14,930
I think Waymo is a solution that's both good and very bad at the same time.

751
00:32:14,930 --> 00:32:16,510
And why is that?

752
00:32:16,510 --> 00:32:18,740
The 'good' part is that I think their technical capabilities are solid.

753
00:32:18,740 --> 00:32:21,220
But I think it will have a hard time going global.

754
00:32:21,220 --> 00:32:23,580
I think, looking at the past,

755
00:32:23,580 --> 00:32:28,530
Level 4 technology is, by its very nature, a more advanced patchwork monster.

756
00:32:28,530 --> 00:32:32,900
It's difficult for it to achieve extremely powerful generalization within AI.

757
00:32:32,900 --> 00:32:35,880
I don't think it's a particularly brilliant methodology.

758
00:32:35,880 --> 00:32:39,740
Of course, Google is doing a lot of things with their new large models now.

759
00:32:39,740 --> 00:32:42,100
But I think that could change in the future.

760
00:32:42,100 --> 00:32:44,250
But as of right now, I haven't really seen that.

761
00:32:44,250 --> 00:32:45,770
So, let's look at it from another angle.

762
00:32:45,770 --> 00:32:47,370
Let me just give a couple of examples, right?

763
00:32:47,370 --> 00:32:50,950
Even just to make driving easier and safer for the driver,

764
00:32:50,950 --> 00:32:52,450
or get to your destination faster.

765
00:32:52,450 --> 00:32:54,020
We're all drivers here.

766
00:32:54,020 --> 00:32:56,720
And I've been working on just that for 17 years now.

767
00:32:56,720 --> 00:33:00,320
No single company has been able to do it exceptionally well.

768
00:33:00,320 --> 00:33:02,120
Alright, let's look at it from another angle.

769
00:33:02,120 --> 00:33:04,370
There are many, many small companies,

770
00:33:04,370 --> 00:33:05,390
with a skeleton crew

771
00:33:05,390 --> 00:33:08,770
teams of just a dozen people saying, 'I'm going to change the world with AI coding'.

772
00:33:08,770 --> 00:33:11,720
Well, I personally think they completely underestimated it.

773
00:33:11,720 --> 00:33:15,640
the diversity and complexity of change in the physical world.

774
00:33:15,640 --> 00:33:18,650
It's like how we started out in the mobile internet era.

775
00:33:18,650 --> 00:33:19,650
and stormed into the auto industry.

776
00:33:19,650 --> 00:33:21,690
Everyone thinks that if I just do one thing to perfection...

777
00:33:21,690 --> 00:33:23,670
And that if we just pushed it a little further, we'd be all set.

778
00:33:23,670 --> 00:33:26,680
No, because you're thinking about it in the wrong dimension.

779
00:33:27,340 --> 00:33:30,200
You're thinking in terms of the digital dimension.

780
00:33:30,200 --> 00:33:32,000
You're just pushing the digital dimension to its absolute limit.

781
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:34,000
its value proposition could be tiny.

782
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:35,960
So, when you made that big bet last year,

783
00:33:35,960 --> 00:33:37,520
Were there any negative voices within the company?

784
00:33:37,520 --> 00:33:38,680
Were there any opposing voices?

785
00:33:38,680 --> 00:33:39,600
Absolutely.

786
00:33:39,600 --> 00:33:44,640
I think most of the non-AI executives felt that...

787
00:33:44,640 --> 00:33:47,550
that no matter if you chose A or B, you'd probably be wrong.

788
00:33:47,830 --> 00:33:50,980
Because back then, their understanding of AI just wasn't strong enough.

789
00:33:50,980 --> 00:33:53,160
I think that for most of the executives involved in AI,

790
00:33:53,160 --> 00:33:54,500
Some people were all in, saying yes.

791
00:33:54,500 --> 00:33:55,300
Others thought it was just... low.

792
00:33:55,300 --> 00:33:57,350
But most of them were somewhere in the middle.

793
00:33:57,550 --> 00:34:00,490
We just weren't sure if we were pacing it right.

794
00:34:00,490 --> 00:34:04,360
They weren't sure if this could actually yield any tangible results.

795
00:34:04,360 --> 00:34:06,420
Honestly, I felt the exact same way back then.

796
00:34:06,420 --> 00:34:08,380
But that's the fun of it, the thrill of entrepreneurship.

797
00:34:08,380 --> 00:34:12,400
I mean, isn't entrepreneurship for everyone all about building on what you're capable of at that very moment?

798
00:34:12,400 --> 00:34:16,199
Are you betting on a 10x, or even a 1000-fold, return?

799
00:34:16,199 --> 00:34:17,499
If you're betting on a 1000x return,

800
00:34:17,499 --> 00:34:19,300
Your odds are just one in a thousand.

801
00:34:19,300 --> 00:34:20,380
But for a 10x return,

802
00:34:20,380 --> 00:34:22,460
then your chances of success might be one in ten.

803
00:34:22,460 --> 00:34:26,340
So it's just like the very first bet you make when you start a business.

804
00:34:26,340 --> 00:34:27,980
As your startup grows in scale,

805
00:34:27,980 --> 00:34:29,409
you still have to take that gamble.

806
00:34:29,409 --> 00:34:32,409
It's just that, at that point, you shouldn't be making a bet with 1000-to-1 odds.

807
00:34:32,409 --> 00:34:34,829
You might be betting on something with odds of, say, a few times to 10 times the return.

808
00:34:34,829 --> 00:34:37,650
So, what was the biggest opposition you've ever faced?

809
00:34:37,650 --> 00:34:41,320
I think the biggest opposition was that a lot of people just voted with their feet.

810
00:34:42,520 --> 00:34:43,620
Well, how should I put it...

811
00:34:43,620 --> 00:34:46,140
What 'voting with their feet' means is very simple.

812
00:34:46,140 --> 00:34:47,340
They just didn't believe it could be done.

813
00:34:47,340 --> 00:34:48,380
They felt it was unachievable.

814
00:34:48,380 --> 00:34:49,700
So, they just left.

815
00:34:49,700 --> 00:34:50,880
to go off and do other things.

816
00:34:50,880 --> 00:34:53,850
I think, when it comes to a company today,

817
00:34:53,850 --> 00:34:56,560
I think when it comes to thinking about an organization...

818
00:34:56,560 --> 00:35:00,960
Just remember, don't try to chop down a giant tree with a tiny knife.

819
00:35:00,960 --> 00:35:03,410
and just chip away at it.

820
00:35:03,410 --> 00:35:06,150
If you've made up your mind, just cut it down.

821
00:35:06,150 --> 00:35:08,890
So, when it comes to certain things, you're willing to place your bet.

822
00:35:08,890 --> 00:35:12,850
From the organizational structure to the workflows,

823
00:35:12,850 --> 00:35:17,290
Right. From the direction, everything had to be changed, completely.

824
00:35:17,290 --> 00:35:20,370
So, the changes you made last year were pretty massive, right?

825
00:35:20,370 --> 00:35:23,510
Right, what people see is probably just the top layer.

826
00:35:23,510 --> 00:35:24,970
the business or application layer.

827
00:35:24,970 --> 00:35:28,050
But internally, what we saw went all the way down to the very root of the problem.

828
00:35:28,050 --> 00:35:29,930
So, this is what I've always wanted to say.

829
00:35:29,930 --> 00:35:34,899
It's incredibly important to figure out how to use AI to drive specific business areas.

830
00:35:34,899 --> 00:35:37,999
rather than using hardware to drive the entire system.

831
00:35:37,999 --> 00:35:42,150
I've listened to many of your shows, and they're basically all about digital AI, right.

832
00:35:42,150 --> 00:35:46,340
Basically, no one in an organization of tens of thousands...

833
00:35:46,340 --> 00:35:51,760
We need to think about AI from the perspective of having extensive, robust interactions with the real physical world.

834
00:35:51,760 --> 00:35:53,070
What I want to say is,

835
00:35:53,070 --> 00:35:56,010
replicating their methodologies into physical AI.

836
00:35:56,010 --> 00:36:00,650
I think there are many aspects where it's just not a good fit.

837
00:36:00,650 --> 00:36:03,349
Maybe some parts of the business logic are correct,

838
00:36:03,349 --> 00:36:05,429
But they're just not comprehensive or thorough enough.

839
00:36:05,429 --> 00:36:06,880
And that was the biggest problem.

840
00:36:06,880 --> 00:36:08,200
So at this point, what I really want to ask you is...

841
00:36:08,200 --> 00:36:10,580
So, how exactly do you develop Physical AI?

842
00:36:10,580 --> 00:36:13,000
and trying to push it forward within an established organization.

843
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:14,500
I don't think I can give you a straight answer on that.

844
00:36:14,500 --> 00:36:16,200
Because I'm still figuring it out myself.

845
00:36:16,200 --> 00:36:17,600
From my perspective,

846
00:36:17,600 --> 00:36:20,980
Right now, there are four major directions in AI.

847
00:36:20,980 --> 00:36:24,850
One is figuring out how digital AI will evolve.

848
00:36:24,850 --> 00:36:28,370
And I think, in this area, you've got a lot of people already thinking about it and taking action.

849
00:36:28,370 --> 00:36:29,970
I think the second one is physical AI.

850
00:36:29,970 --> 00:36:31,910
And it's probably 100 times harder than digital AI.

851
00:36:31,910 --> 00:36:35,140
But I think starting from 2027 or 2028,

852
00:36:35,140 --> 00:36:38,200
People will start to see the impact of Physical AI.

853
00:36:38,760 --> 00:36:44,010
We'll start to see things similar to ChatGPT,

854
00:36:44,010 --> 00:36:47,130
and massive changes in digital AI, like what we're seeing with Anthropic.

855
00:36:47,130 --> 00:36:51,360
In other words, which specific jobs has it provided significant help for?

856
00:36:51,360 --> 00:36:54,320
and possibly even replacement in the long run.

857
00:36:54,320 --> 00:36:55,840
So, that's the second point.

858
00:36:55,840 --> 00:37:00,600
And the second point is, I don't think anyone today has truly...

859
00:37:00,600 --> 00:37:04,580
I think, aside from Google working on AI for the human body,

860
00:37:04,580 --> 00:37:06,780
and couple the two very well.

861
00:37:06,780 --> 00:37:12,160
Because the pharmaceutical industry is an incredibly complex field.

862
00:37:12,160 --> 00:37:13,280
including elderly care.

863
00:37:13,280 --> 00:37:15,520
I think for the human body, it's not just about the internal circulation.

864
00:37:15,520 --> 00:37:16,360
but also the external ones.

865
00:37:16,360 --> 00:37:17,720
And the fourth point, I think, is a really tough one.

866
00:37:17,720 --> 00:37:21,540
The question is, how do you couple a company with AI?

867
00:37:21,540 --> 00:37:25,600
Actually, integrating AI into specific departments or centralized hubs is relatively straightforward.

868
00:37:25,600 --> 00:37:26,760
But for a company as a whole, that's a much bigger challenge.

869
00:37:26,760 --> 00:37:29,130
But what I'm seeing now is that there are a lot of smaller companies,

870
00:37:29,130 --> 00:37:30,930
the ones with probably under 1,000 employees,

871
00:37:30,930 --> 00:37:33,450
I feel like they're starting to explore more.

872
00:37:33,450 --> 00:37:34,870
And I think that's a really great point.

873
00:37:34,870 --> 00:37:37,530
Actually, we are also constantly observing and learning.

874
00:37:37,530 --> 00:37:39,510
and will do the same when the time is right.

875
00:37:39,510 --> 00:37:40,950
So, I believe that for corporate AI...

876
00:37:40,950 --> 00:37:44,190
So today, this presents an opportunity for companies of all sizes.

877
00:37:44,190 --> 00:37:46,870
So, for a company like XPeng right now,

878
00:37:46,870 --> 00:37:48,150
So this is a period of transformation for you as well, isn't it?

879
00:37:48,150 --> 00:37:51,390
Yes, and it's going to be a period of transformation for the long haul.

880
00:37:51,390 --> 00:37:54,090
Technological changes, on the other hand, can happen in the span of a month.

881
00:37:54,670 --> 00:37:55,960
But for an organization to change...

882
00:37:55,960 --> 00:37:58,020
And I'm not talking about a small organization here.

883
00:37:58,020 --> 00:38:00,960
First of all, if we're talking about a global, mid-sized organization,

884
00:38:00,960 --> 00:38:05,540
I think to get it all done in three years would be an incredibly terrifying pace.

885
00:38:05,540 --> 00:38:09,800
I'd even say that 5 to 10 years is already considered fast.

886
00:38:09,800 --> 00:38:12,680
In an era of such radical technological transformation,

887
00:38:12,680 --> 00:38:13,860
Do you feel anxious?

888
00:38:13,860 --> 00:38:15,020
being a CEO,

889
00:38:15,020 --> 00:38:17,500
Of course I am. And just how anxious?

890
00:38:17,500 --> 00:38:20,620
Because you'll find that a lot of your previous logic...

891
00:38:20,620 --> 00:38:23,080
and even the very foundation of your logic,

892
00:38:23,080 --> 00:38:28,560
the paradigms and principles you once held sacred,

893
00:38:28,560 --> 00:38:29,960
or even deeper,

894
00:38:29,960 --> 00:38:31,340
perhaps even down to the axiomatic level.

895
00:38:31,340 --> 00:38:33,560
Basically, your values, your philosophy on life, and your worldview.

896
00:38:33,560 --> 00:38:37,510
you'll feel that with all these changes,

897
00:38:37,510 --> 00:38:41,760
It’s like the old logic just doesn't work anymore.

898
00:38:41,880 --> 00:38:43,440
But the question is, what's the new logic? How is it supposed to work?

899
00:38:43,440 --> 00:38:48,380
Remember, there's a difference between seeing a problem, solving a problem, and building a system to...

900
00:38:48,380 --> 00:38:53,200
and avoiding problems in a way that sets a high ceiling while also preventing a low floor.

901
00:38:53,200 --> 00:38:55,670
These are three completely different levels of capability.

902
00:38:55,930 --> 00:38:57,310
A lot of people just spot problems.

903
00:38:57,310 --> 00:38:59,030
You know, back in the day, before I started my own business,

904
00:38:59,030 --> 00:39:00,480
I also see countless problems.

905
00:39:00,480 --> 00:39:02,340
But when you're an entrepreneur,

906
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:07,859
You'll find that a lot of problems, they're just supposed to be there.

907
00:39:07,859 --> 00:39:09,659
You simply can't solve the problem.

908
00:39:09,659 --> 00:39:10,419
You're a CEO.

909
00:39:10,419 --> 00:39:11,259
you still can't solve them.

910
00:39:11,259 --> 00:39:13,619
Even if you're someone with greater authority,

911
00:39:13,619 --> 00:39:14,599
you can't solve it either.

912
00:39:14,599 --> 00:39:18,950
Because the problem you're seeing is just one small part, from a single perspective, of a much bigger global issue.

913
00:39:18,950 --> 00:39:21,510
Uh-huh.

914
00:39:21,510 --> 00:39:23,390
So, this is a really fascinating topic.

915
00:39:23,390 --> 00:39:24,590
So, about that anxiety you were just talking about...

916
00:39:24,590 --> 00:39:27,250
That means you're constantly having to rebuild your own theorems.

917
00:39:27,250 --> 00:39:30,470
Or even axioms. What kind of axioms from the past have you had to推翻?

918
00:39:30,470 --> 00:39:33,760
What were some things you believed in very firmly in the past?

919
00:39:33,760 --> 00:39:35,960
And now, we feel like it just doesn't work in this day and age.

920
00:39:35,960 --> 00:39:37,900
Let me give you an example that's not related to this...

921
00:39:37,900 --> 00:39:40,060
But let me give you an example that's only slightly related.

922
00:39:40,060 --> 00:39:44,190
Take XPeng's work on autonomous driving, for example.

923
00:39:44,190 --> 00:39:45,710
After working on it for many years,

924
00:39:45,710 --> 00:39:46,870
The more you work on it,

925
00:39:46,870 --> 00:39:52,000
the more you feel like Level 5 is just never going to happen, right?

926
00:39:52,000 --> 00:40:00,020
Because when you think about it, using software to cover every scenario, every regulation in the world... and the human-machine interaction—I'm talking about HMI,

927
00:40:00,020 --> 00:40:03,360
Or, to be more precise, I'm talking about the 'human' in 'human-machine interaction'.

928
00:40:03,360 --> 00:40:04,960
It's the interaction between humans and the world.

929
00:40:04,960 --> 00:40:07,450
You'll find it's just an endless loop.

930
00:40:07,650 --> 00:40:11,730
But when you actually use AI to completely rebuild this from the ground up,

931
00:40:11,730 --> 00:40:16,269
Once you start to believe it's actually possible,

932
00:40:16,269 --> 00:40:18,109
And when you think it might actually be possible,

933
00:40:18,109 --> 00:40:23,820
You start to see many of the so-called old barriers and conventional logic in a completely new light.

934
00:40:23,820 --> 00:40:26,290
Ah...

935
00:40:26,290 --> 00:40:27,730
That's all I can say on the matter for now.

936
00:40:27,730 --> 00:40:28,690
So I won't go into more detail.

937
00:40:28,690 --> 00:40:30,250
Speaking of AI, let's not talk about cars first.

938
00:40:30,250 --> 00:40:33,130
Because the automotive industry is a well-established business that's been around for a very long time.

939
00:40:33,130 --> 00:40:34,770
So, let's start with your robots.

940
00:40:34,770 --> 00:40:37,930
Your robot made quite a splash last year, both in China and internationally.

941
00:40:37,930 --> 00:40:39,910
Could you tell us the story of how this product came to be?

942
00:40:39,910 --> 00:40:44,400
So, I heard that back in 2023...

943
00:40:44,400 --> 00:40:46,580
So you've bet big on the direction of general-purpose humanoid robots, is that right?

944
00:40:46,580 --> 00:40:49,240
Actually, XPeng's robotics development can be broken down into three stages.

945
00:40:49,240 --> 00:40:52,440
The first one was from 2018 to 2020.

946
00:40:52,440 --> 00:40:53,920
It was an independent team.

947
00:40:53,920 --> 00:40:57,160
Back then, it was just like many other robotics teams in China.

948
00:40:57,160 --> 00:41:01,220
And you were the one who acquired them, right? It was around that time, there were about four or five companies all working on quadrupeds.

949
00:41:01,220 --> 00:41:02,680
So, what about 2020?

950
00:41:02,680 --> 00:41:06,450
Then, 2023 marked the beginning of our second phase.

951
00:41:06,450 --> 00:41:10,090
So, it took us about three and a half to four years.

952
00:41:10,090 --> 00:41:13,890
We reached three different milestones.

953
00:41:13,890 --> 00:41:15,330
I think it was, uh...

954
00:41:15,330 --> 00:41:16,410
I think that was the second phase.

955
00:41:16,410 --> 00:41:17,810
We tried a lot of things within this process.

956
00:41:17,810 --> 00:41:20,500
We tried making robots the 'robotic' way,

957
00:41:20,500 --> 00:41:22,240
We tried integrating them using our automotive approach,

958
00:41:22,240 --> 00:41:24,780
and at times, we even tried to stitch different approaches together to build our robots.

959
00:41:24,780 --> 00:41:28,300
We've had our share of both successes and failures with each approach.

960
00:41:28,300 --> 00:41:32,100
Then, after 2023, it was a whole new ball game, a completely different logic.

961
00:41:32,100 --> 00:41:37,530
Then in 2022, we saw this new model.

962
00:41:37,530 --> 00:41:39,790
We thought that for robots, creating a successful 'brain' was simply impossible.

963
00:41:39,790 --> 00:41:42,700
meaning the chances of succeeding without a brain were zero.

964
00:41:42,700 --> 00:41:45,820
Because, in reality, the complexity of the cerebellum is far beyond what most people think.

965
00:41:45,820 --> 00:41:49,000
You know, a lot of people are saying today that the cerebellum for robots is already a done deal.

966
00:41:49,000 --> 00:41:50,660
I was like, that's not a cerebellum.

967
00:41:50,660 --> 00:41:53,700
They just take these slow, monotonous steps forward.

968
00:41:53,700 --> 00:41:55,200
I don't think that's the cerebellum.

969
00:41:55,200 --> 00:41:59,830
That's the spinal cord, or your brainstem, just keeping you balanced.

970
00:41:59,830 --> 00:42:01,870
You're not even close to having a cerebellum.

971
00:42:01,870 --> 00:42:03,490
They said that's also part of the cerebellum.

972
00:42:03,490 --> 00:42:06,270
He said that the cerebellum for your movements is actually your cerebrum.

973
00:42:06,270 --> 00:42:07,320
OK, anyway...

974
00:42:07,320 --> 00:42:09,840
I think it's really just a matter of different statistical logic, you know?

975
00:42:09,840 --> 00:42:11,360
So, after 2023...

976
00:42:11,360 --> 00:42:17,990
XPeng's robots are now making a fresh push, decisively shifting from quadrupeds to bipeds.

977
00:42:17,990 --> 00:42:19,870
We went from not believing in the brain...

978
00:42:19,870 --> 00:42:22,100
Just like how we didn't believe in Level 5 back then.

979
00:42:22,100 --> 00:42:23,640
and we're now firmly committed.

980
00:42:23,640 --> 00:42:27,310
It's a completely new design, one where the brain drives the robot.

981
00:42:27,310 --> 00:42:29,490
And when you add to that what we've seen in the automotive industry...

982
00:42:29,490 --> 00:42:31,870
Good technology doesn't necessarily mean a good product.

983
00:42:31,870 --> 00:42:33,570
And a great product doesn't necessarily mean you have a great commodity.

984
00:42:33,570 --> 00:42:35,450
And just because you have a great product, doesn't mean you can scale it up.

985
00:42:35,450 --> 00:42:37,950
Because the auto industry has a very well-established...

986
00:42:37,950 --> 00:42:46,140
It's an entire process, from planning and design, to ET, PT, SOP, and SOD.

987
00:42:46,140 --> 00:42:48,200
In fact, by the end of this year,

988
00:42:48,200 --> 00:42:51,520
So we're hoping to reach the robot's own 'SOP' stage, similar to the automotive process.

989
00:42:51,520 --> 00:42:54,160
So, looking ahead to 2027, that will very likely be the year for advanced-level robots.

990
00:42:54,160 --> 00:42:55,870
for high-level humanoid robots.

991
00:42:55,870 --> 00:42:58,950
and mark the first year of commercial mass production.

992
00:42:58,950 --> 00:43:01,890
Both China and the U.S. will be heavily invested in training.

993
00:43:01,890 --> 00:43:07,499
I think, in the past, during the era of motion-and-remote-controlled robots,

994
00:43:07,499 --> 00:43:09,719
that's going to change with the emergence of advanced robots.

995
00:43:09,719 --> 00:43:12,440
will gradually decline to some extent.

996
00:43:12,440 --> 00:43:14,380
I think we're entering a phase where the paths will diverge.

997
00:43:14,380 --> 00:43:16,820
In reality, everyone is looking forward to physical AI.

998
00:43:16,820 --> 00:43:19,970
And the most quintessential example of this is robots.

999
00:43:19,970 --> 00:43:23,930
in what ways can it help humanity, and what kind of value can it truly deliver?

1000
00:43:23,930 --> 00:43:25,290
To be able to do work.

1001
00:43:25,290 --> 00:43:28,030
In the past, that value was primarily emotional.

1002
00:43:28,030 --> 00:43:30,190
Right, and that emotional value is valuable in its own right.

1003
00:43:30,190 --> 00:43:32,990
But what's even more important is the combination of physical value and emotional value.

1004
00:43:32,990 --> 00:43:35,020
Ah.

1005
00:43:35,020 --> 00:43:36,920
So, I think next year could be the year it all begins.

1006
00:43:36,920 --> 00:43:38,520
So what happened in 2023?

1007
00:43:38,520 --> 00:43:39,440
So it went from something you didn't believe in to something you do.

1008
00:43:39,440 --> 00:43:43,060
In 2023, I think it was because at that time...

1009
00:43:43,060 --> 00:43:47,360
If we were to use a team that's really knowledgeable about robotics,

1010
00:43:47,360 --> 00:43:49,150
a team we were very familiar with,

1011
00:43:49,150 --> 00:43:53,550
we wouldn't have the capability to develop a good, brand-new generation of robots.

1012
00:43:53,550 --> 00:43:54,910
We were using lidar at the time.

1013
00:43:54,910 --> 00:44:00,330
So, out of our team of 300 people, we ended up keeping fewer than 60.

1014
00:44:00,330 --> 00:44:02,990
So we disbanded it, and they all left.

1015
00:44:02,990 --> 00:44:06,290
I heard that, out of them, about 10 teams went on to start their own companies.

1016
00:44:06,290 --> 00:44:07,410
And most of them have actually raised funding by now.

1017
00:44:07,410 --> 00:44:11,150
For instance, Masslytics has raised a ton of money in multiple rounds.

1018
00:44:11,150 --> 00:44:15,850
In my opinion, we have to fundamentally rethink the entire logic of robotics.

1019
00:44:15,850 --> 00:44:19,750
But at the same time, we can't just use the old-school robotics folks either.

1020
00:44:19,750 --> 00:44:21,410
But on the other hand, they can't know nothing at all either.

1021
00:44:21,410 --> 00:44:23,540
So, what kind of people should we hire then?

1022
00:44:23,820 --> 00:44:24,680
I didn't know.

1023
00:44:24,680 --> 00:44:28,850
So that's why, at that point, I decided to go with a completely new team.

1024
00:44:28,850 --> 00:44:30,390
Someone who knows a bit about AI,

1025
00:44:30,390 --> 00:44:33,930
and knew a thing or two about engineering.

1026
00:44:33,930 --> 00:44:35,510
and knew a thing or two about robotics.

1027
00:44:35,510 --> 00:44:39,870
And then try to build a completely new way of thinking about robotics.

1028
00:44:39,870 --> 00:44:41,430
So why did they pick him back then?

1029
00:44:41,430 --> 00:44:43,370
I think a lot of the time, it just comes down to fate.

1030
00:44:43,370 --> 00:44:45,950
I mean, you can't say that just because he wasn't a robotics expert

1031
00:44:45,950 --> 00:44:47,870
He wasn't a specialist in smart driving, either.

1032
00:44:47,870 --> 00:44:48,790
So, I chose him, right?

1033
00:44:48,790 --> 00:44:50,680
He's really neither.

1034
00:44:50,680 --> 00:44:57,900
At that time, I felt that his way of thinking was in a similar quadrant to my own.

1035
00:44:58,940 --> 00:45:04,230
So, he was one of the few people I had in mind within that particular quadrant.

1036
00:45:04,230 --> 00:45:05,630
First, you have to choose him.

1037
00:45:05,630 --> 00:45:06,910
He has to choose you too.

1038
00:45:06,910 --> 00:45:08,990
His choice, back at you.

1039
00:45:08,990 --> 00:45:12,020
I think we can give it a try.

1040
00:45:12,020 --> 00:45:15,520
So, I often see a lot of robot demos or presentations from other companies out there.

1041
00:45:15,520 --> 00:45:16,700
or videos,

1042
00:45:16,700 --> 00:45:19,320
And I always say, a lot of their work is still on our...

1043
00:45:19,320 --> 00:45:25,330
maybe on our third or fourth-gen tech stack, to do some testing.

1044
00:45:25,330 --> 00:45:27,570
I mean, for me, maybe he can succeed.

1045
00:45:27,570 --> 00:45:28,650
But I've been there, I've tried it.

1046
00:45:28,650 --> 00:45:32,260
So, I believe that for XPeng, in this continuous process of innovation,

1047
00:45:32,260 --> 00:45:35,760
We are a company that has both patience and courage.

1048
00:45:35,760 --> 00:45:37,220
and commit to it for the long haul.

1049
00:45:37,220 --> 00:45:39,180
So, you see a lot of robotics companies today,

1050
00:45:39,180 --> 00:45:41,100
They can whip up a demo really quickly,

1051
00:45:41,100 --> 00:45:42,280
That's nothing.

1052
00:45:42,280 --> 00:45:43,310
The way I see it,

1053
00:45:43,310 --> 00:45:45,290
It's just like back in 2017.

1054
00:45:45,290 --> 00:45:47,850
Back then in China, there were a ton of Level 4 data companies.

1055
00:45:47,850 --> 00:45:49,650
It's just like the robotics scene today.

1056
00:45:49,650 --> 00:45:51,050
Of course, there are way more in the robotics space.

1057
00:45:51,050 --> 00:45:54,310
In reality, that doesn't represent the technologies themselves.

1058
00:45:54,310 --> 00:45:56,870
so that you can ultimately see its real value.

1059
00:45:56,870 --> 00:46:00,390
It's just a simple analogy, I guess.

1060
00:46:00,390 --> 00:46:02,310
Because that's not really a fair comparison either.

1061
00:46:02,310 --> 00:46:04,690
So you've chosen the person to lead the robotics division.

1062
00:46:04,690 --> 00:46:08,920
Did that have any impact on your later hiring criteria?

1063
00:46:08,920 --> 00:46:11,580
So do you think that's a formula you can stick with?

1064
00:46:11,580 --> 00:46:12,640
Because of what you just brought up,

1065
00:46:12,640 --> 00:46:15,400
It makes me think of Elon Musk, who has a real preference for hiring generalists.

1066
00:46:15,400 --> 00:46:17,620
He's not a fan of specialists.

1067
00:46:17,620 --> 00:46:22,099
I suppose maybe at Tesla's location in Silicon Valley,

1068
00:46:22,099 --> 00:46:25,599
it's probably easier to find a bigger pool of generalists to choose from.

1069
00:46:25,599 --> 00:46:27,759
I think, in most countries,

1070
00:46:27,759 --> 00:46:30,650
it's very difficult for any city or industry.

1071
00:46:30,650 --> 00:46:31,950
So, that's the first thing.

1072
00:46:31,950 --> 00:46:35,590
I think what Elon Musk emphasizes a lot, in his own words, is what he calls 'talent density.'

1073
00:46:35,590 --> 00:46:37,270
Yeah.

1074
00:46:37,270 --> 00:46:39,730
I actually think it's about the potential of the talent.

1075
00:46:39,730 --> 00:46:42,580
He basically hires only the best people.

1076
00:46:42,580 --> 00:46:44,960
For instance, from the end of last year to the first half of this year,

1077
00:46:44,960 --> 00:46:48,330
We primarily hire master's and PhD graduates from top-tier universities.

1078
00:46:48,330 --> 00:46:50,730
In one department alone, we hired almost 80 of them.

1079
00:46:50,730 --> 00:46:52,430
And they are all very expensive.

1080
00:46:52,430 --> 00:46:54,210
But we were all willing to do it.

1081
00:46:54,210 --> 00:46:57,170
And on top of that, you have to have the ability to bring a group of people like this together.

1082
00:46:57,170 --> 00:47:00,279
And you have to be willing to support them in their long-term exploration.

1083
00:47:00,279 --> 00:47:05,410
You have to believe in this group of young guys, and girls.

1084
00:47:05,410 --> 00:47:07,070
They're the ones who can create miracles.

1085
00:47:07,070 --> 00:47:08,770
I think it's about the potential of talent.

1086
00:47:08,770 --> 00:47:10,150
He believes it's about the caliber of the talent.

1087
00:47:10,150 --> 00:47:16,880
I believe you need exceptionally smart people to tackle exceptionally difficult problems.

1088
00:47:16,880 --> 00:47:20,840
rather than relying on a very clear direction or a set process.

1089
00:47:20,840 --> 00:47:24,870
or tools to shape them.

1090
00:47:24,870 --> 00:47:27,230
And I think, for certain stages, that's absolutely the right approach.

1091
00:47:27,230 --> 00:47:29,490
At that time, we had to bet on general-purpose humanoid robots.

1092
00:47:29,490 --> 00:47:31,290
So, what was your reasoning behind that choice?

1093
00:47:31,290 --> 00:47:33,990
So, back in 2023, why was it that it *had* to be a general-purpose humanoid robot?

1094
00:47:33,990 --> 00:47:35,790
I think this is a path every company has to choose for itself.

1095
00:47:38,160 --> 00:47:40,829
And it's the same for my team and I, myself.

1096
00:47:40,829 --> 00:47:42,489
LC is even crazier than I am.

1097
00:47:42,489 --> 00:47:44,849
He's always been telling me that he wants to create people,

1098
00:47:44,849 --> 00:47:45,909
not just a robot.

1099
00:47:45,909 --> 00:47:49,090
The thing is, most people just see a robot as a commercial product.

1100
00:47:49,090 --> 00:47:52,450
But what I think they haven't considered is, in the end, what role will robots play in our society?

1101
00:47:52,450 --> 00:47:54,850
or their sense of participation in this universe.

1102
00:47:54,850 --> 00:47:57,550
or its connection to the emotional value for each and every one of us.

1103
00:47:57,550 --> 00:47:59,500
It's just like back in 2014,

1104
00:47:59,500 --> 00:48:02,560
Many people feel that the 'smart' in smart cars is actually of no real value.

1105
00:48:02,560 --> 00:48:03,860
And I think even today, there are still a lot of people...

1106
00:48:03,860 --> 00:48:07,100
First, they don't believe that general-purpose robots will ever arrive.

1107
00:48:07,100 --> 00:48:11,040
And second, they simply don't want to see that general-purpose robots might arrive in, say, 20 or 50 years.

1108
00:48:11,040 --> 00:48:13,960
Maybe in 20 or 50 years.

1109
00:48:13,960 --> 00:48:18,450
It will be deeply intertwined with every facet of human life.

1110
00:48:18,450 --> 00:48:22,650
The digital AI we were just discussing, it's really just there to assist humans.

1111
00:48:22,650 --> 00:48:25,590
Maybe three main categories of jobs.

1112
00:48:25,590 --> 00:48:28,390
And maybe dozens of other, more niche job branches.

1113
00:48:28,390 --> 00:48:30,550
But physical AI is on a whole different scale.

1114
00:48:30,550 --> 00:48:32,880
The scale could be tens, or even hundreds of times larger.

1115
00:48:32,880 --> 00:48:34,280
Everyone gets old.

1116
00:48:34,280 --> 00:48:37,180
Actually, for me, a really crucial point when it comes to robots is...

1117
00:48:37,180 --> 00:48:39,710
The future of robots for the elderly.

1118
00:48:39,710 --> 00:48:42,390
I think these are the two most critical factors, absolutely.

1119
00:48:42,390 --> 00:48:45,610
I think the first factor is this concept of embodied AI.

1120
00:48:45,610 --> 00:48:47,939
How to keep the elderly from getting sick

1121
00:48:47,939 --> 00:48:50,119
Live longer, and live happier.

1122
00:48:50,119 --> 00:48:52,910
And the second point, which I think is about physical AI,

1123
00:48:52,910 --> 00:48:55,220
The impact robots will have on the elderly will be immense.

1124
00:48:55,220 --> 00:48:58,140
It's very likely that for the elderly, a robot will become their one and only support.

1125
00:48:58,140 --> 00:48:59,860
I think very few people would think that way.

1126
00:48:59,860 --> 00:49:01,660
I think XPeng's approach to robotics thinking...

1127
00:49:01,660 --> 00:49:02,980
is quite different from many other companies.

1128
00:49:02,980 --> 00:49:06,420
That explosive discussion last year, did it catch you off guard?

1129
00:49:06,420 --> 00:49:07,850
You seemed pretty aggrieved at the time.

1130
00:49:07,850 --> 00:49:09,350
Yeah, it took us completely by surprise.

1131
00:49:09,350 --> 00:49:11,850
Our thinking was actually very technical.

1132
00:49:11,850 --> 00:49:13,290
Because, regarding that robot from last year...

1133
00:49:13,290 --> 00:49:16,470
We actually started working on it in the first quarter of the year before last.

1134
00:49:16,470 --> 00:49:19,130
For us, this is just an intermediate version.

1135
00:49:19,130 --> 00:49:22,050
So, with this intermediate version, we just wanted to validate...

1136
00:49:22,050 --> 00:49:25,770
If a robot had as many joints as a human,

1137
00:49:25,770 --> 00:49:28,070
In fact, it still has far fewer joints than a human.

1138
00:49:28,070 --> 00:49:29,750
A human has, what, over 200 joints?

1139
00:49:29,750 --> 00:49:31,230
and muscles, too.

1140
00:49:31,230 --> 00:49:32,430
and skin too.

1141
00:49:32,430 --> 00:49:33,730
And I can tell you this,

1142
00:49:33,730 --> 00:49:37,510
A lot of the robots we see today, their walking ability,

1143
00:49:37,510 --> 00:49:40,030
Once it has muscles and skin on its body,

1144
00:49:40,030 --> 00:49:43,300
its walking performance would change and degrade significantly.

1145
00:49:43,300 --> 00:49:45,340
Because that's a completely different ball game.

1146
00:49:45,340 --> 00:49:47,870
Look at it from another angle, we just want to explore the possibilities.

1147
00:49:47,870 --> 00:49:49,130
So, in a situation like this,

1148
00:49:49,130 --> 00:49:53,740
Could it find its way into our lives more easily?

1149
00:49:53,740 --> 00:49:55,580
or into our work and our emotional lives,

1150
00:49:55,580 --> 00:49:56,540
Let me give you an example.

1151
00:49:56,540 --> 00:49:58,470
Take the quadruped robot we made before, for example.

1152
00:49:58,470 --> 00:50:00,090
We made a dog-shaped one, and a horse-shaped one.

1153
00:50:00,090 --> 00:50:02,090
No matter what kind of four-legged thing it is,

1154
00:50:02,090 --> 00:50:04,310
it would be a problem just getting it into your room.

1155
00:50:04,310 --> 00:50:11,510
Imagine if you had a robotic dog, about one-point-one to one-point-two meters long,

1156
00:50:11,510 --> 00:50:14,310
or so, gets into your room,

1157
00:50:14,310 --> 00:50:16,610
And once it's in your room, you're going to have a lot of problems, really fast.

1158
00:50:16,610 --> 00:50:18,790
Let's say it's over by your nightstand,

1159
00:50:18,790 --> 00:50:21,029
It can't make a U-turn on the spot.

1160
00:50:21,029 --> 00:50:23,229
Let's say you have a golden retriever at home.

1161
00:50:23,229 --> 00:50:24,549
When it tries to turn around,

1162
00:50:24,549 --> 00:50:27,969
its tail will give a little flick upwards.

1163
00:50:27,969 --> 00:50:29,149
It'll lift it up.

1164
00:50:29,149 --> 00:50:31,640
And it's going to scrape against the wall and your bed.

1165
00:50:31,640 --> 00:50:35,220
And you wouldn't feel like your bed got hurt either.

1166
00:50:35,220 --> 00:50:36,840
But a robotic dog,

1167
00:50:36,840 --> 00:50:39,880
100%, it's gonna leave both of you feeling bruised.

1168
00:50:40,200 --> 00:50:41,800
So, what if you make the dog smaller?

1169
00:50:41,800 --> 00:50:43,440
If you make it really small...

1170
00:50:44,480 --> 00:50:46,910
its capabilities would be incredibly limited.

1171
00:50:46,910 --> 00:50:48,730
It's basically just for light companionship.

1172
00:50:48,730 --> 00:50:50,410
Another issue is the battery life; it's extremely short.

1173
00:50:50,410 --> 00:50:51,350
So, that's the first point.

1174
00:50:51,350 --> 00:50:52,290
And for the second point...

1175
00:50:52,290 --> 00:50:54,510
So, if it's a bipedal robot,

1176
00:50:54,510 --> 00:50:56,190
and it's got this full-body armor.

1177
00:50:56,190 --> 00:50:57,730
Very imposing, standing at 1.8 meters tall.

1178
00:50:57,730 --> 00:51:02,040
So, 1.8 meters, okay. So, today, even if you're standing right next to it...

1179
00:51:02,040 --> 00:51:03,400
And you're the one who designed it.

1180
00:51:03,400 --> 00:51:07,380
And you wouldn't want to walk right next to it, maybe just an inch apart.

1181
00:51:07,380 --> 00:51:08,660
It feels oppressive.

1182
00:51:08,660 --> 00:51:11,399
You think it might be dangerous.

1183
00:51:11,399 --> 00:51:13,559
You might think it's going to be hot.

1184
00:51:13,559 --> 00:51:15,600
You might think it's electric.

1185
00:51:15,600 --> 00:51:17,240
Or you might think it's dirty.

1186
00:51:17,240 --> 00:51:18,680
Anyway, there are all sorts of reasons.

1187
00:51:18,680 --> 00:51:20,140
You'd keep your distance from it.

1188
00:51:20,140 --> 00:51:22,980
So if even adults like us would react that way,

1189
00:51:22,980 --> 00:51:25,270
So what about the elderly and children?

1190
00:51:25,270 --> 00:51:28,870
And when it comes to their safety and the legal regulations in society, how are we supposed to tackle those issues?

1191
00:51:28,870 --> 00:51:32,230
For industrial robots, you could structure the logic in this way.

1192
00:51:32,230 --> 00:51:35,820
Because it's inherently not designed for home or commercial use.

1193
00:51:35,820 --> 00:51:38,060
So, when it comes to industrial robots, a lot of people...

1194
00:51:38,060 --> 00:51:41,100
He said, 'I've sidestepped the A, B, and C problems.'

1195
00:51:41,100 --> 00:51:42,800
Everything I just talked about was the problem of A, B, and C.

1196
00:51:42,800 --> 00:51:45,220
But industrial robots, in reality, introduce a new problem.

1197
00:51:45,220 --> 00:51:47,420
Essentially, the dexterity of the hands has to be incredibly advanced.

1198
00:51:47,420 --> 00:51:49,820
This introduces a whole new set of problems.

1199
00:51:49,820 --> 00:51:51,910
But let me circle back to what I was saying.

1200
00:51:51,910 --> 00:51:53,450
And looking ahead,

1201
00:51:53,450 --> 00:51:55,859
If robots were to integrate into human society,

1202
00:51:55,859 --> 00:51:57,519
across a wide range of jobs,

1203
00:51:57,519 --> 00:52:01,650
it will create value for both blue-collar and entry-level white-collar jobs

1204
00:52:01,650 --> 00:52:04,050
It absolutely has to become part of our daily lives.

1205
00:52:04,050 --> 00:52:07,590
So, we've chosen a very difficult path.

1206
00:52:07,590 --> 00:52:09,990
So, from my perspective,

1207
00:52:09,990 --> 00:52:12,370
Many robotics companies in China today...

1208
00:52:12,370 --> 00:52:17,079
whether it's in quality or safety,

1209
00:52:17,079 --> 00:52:18,239
Take the recent sports games, for example.

1210
00:52:18,239 --> 00:52:21,979
So you can see, even just with thermal management, you get such an interesting phenomenon.

1211
00:52:21,979 --> 00:52:24,940
Or whether it's about the brain's logic of thought?

1212
00:52:24,940 --> 00:52:29,420
Or rather, it's about how it transitions into the thought process of true physical AI.

1213
00:52:29,420 --> 00:52:32,980
I think we probably saw this coming two or three years ago.

1214
00:52:32,980 --> 00:52:34,680
and we were already making adjustments.

1215
00:52:34,680 --> 00:52:36,920
But we chose a very painful path.

1216
00:52:36,920 --> 00:52:38,970
The deeper you look into this path,

1217
00:52:38,970 --> 00:52:40,330
the harder it is to achieve.

1218
00:52:40,330 --> 00:52:42,430
So why not create some intermediate steps?

1219
00:52:42,430 --> 00:52:45,660
I think we're already doing that intermediate stage.

1220
00:52:45,660 --> 00:52:48,120
What we mean by an intermediate stage is simply...

1221
00:52:48,120 --> 00:52:52,779
If you want to make a robot that can truly generalize and be easily integrated into our human world...

1222
00:52:52,779 --> 00:52:56,179
We're already opting for the easiest intermediate form to build.

1223
00:52:56,179 --> 00:52:57,719
So, how tall should this person be?

1224
00:52:57,719 --> 00:53:00,150
So, take a look at our current generation of robots.

1225
00:53:00,150 --> 00:53:02,790
Somewhere between 1.69 and 1.70 meters.

1226
00:53:02,790 --> 00:53:06,070
It needs to be a height that's comfortable for both men and women.

1227
00:53:06,070 --> 00:53:08,550
Right, and it needs to be able to wear clothes.

1228
00:53:08,550 --> 00:53:09,770
It even has hair.

1229
00:53:09,770 --> 00:53:12,580
But it can't have its own face.

1230
00:53:12,580 --> 00:53:15,699
It has to be clearly distinct from a human.

1231
00:53:15,699 --> 00:53:16,919
And why can't it have its own face?

1232
00:53:16,919 --> 00:53:18,659
Part of it is the uncanny valley effect.

1233
00:53:18,659 --> 00:53:21,739
And some are other factors, like legal and sociological implications.

1234
00:53:21,739 --> 00:53:25,130
So, in reality, the XPeng robot that everyone is seeing right now...

1235
00:53:25,130 --> 00:53:28,090
is still quite different from the robot we at XPeng are currently developing.

1236
00:53:28,090 --> 00:53:30,110
I think we'll have to wait until the second half of this year.

1237
00:53:30,110 --> 00:53:34,090
What I'm looking forward to is a period of very deep, thoughtful consideration for us.

1238
00:53:34,090 --> 00:53:37,620
developed the simplest intermediate stage first.

1239
00:53:37,980 --> 00:53:39,720
And then, we'll channel the full force of the entire company.

1240
00:53:39,720 --> 00:53:41,780
to ensure that the entire company can execute it well.

1241
00:53:41,780 --> 00:53:43,180
So, that's where we stand right now.

1242
00:53:43,180 --> 00:53:45,060
At last year's press conference, you mentioned you were really struggling with a decision.

1243
00:53:45,060 --> 00:53:46,880
Whether or not to prove that there's a real person in there.

1244
00:53:46,880 --> 00:53:48,000
whether I should cut it open for everyone to see.

1245
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:49,000
So why were you so hesitant?

1246
00:53:49,000 --> 00:53:49,760
What's the hesitation?

1247
00:53:49,760 --> 00:53:50,800
Actually, I'm not conflicted about it at all.

1248
00:53:50,800 --> 00:53:52,670
My team, on the other hand, was very conflicted.

1249
00:53:52,670 --> 00:53:55,970
My view was that we had to say it right away. My team, on the other hand...

1250
00:53:55,970 --> 00:53:59,870
The more you try to explain, the more people will think you're the one with the problem.

1251
00:53:59,870 --> 00:54:02,279
Because you'd think that the truth will out on its own.

1252
00:54:02,279 --> 00:54:03,479
and the guilty can't hide their guilt.

1253
00:54:03,479 --> 00:54:05,099
So, that was one perspective from the team.

1254
00:54:05,099 --> 00:54:08,090
The second perspective from the team is to wait and see.

1255
00:54:08,090 --> 00:54:10,330
Let's wait 24 hours.

1256
00:54:10,330 --> 00:54:13,050
Let's see... should I say it or not? I waited for a few hours,

1257
00:54:13,050 --> 00:54:13,810
I just couldn't take it anymore.

1258
00:54:13,810 --> 00:54:14,730
I said, in China...

1259
00:54:14,730 --> 00:54:17,930
This is a hot topic of discussion all over the world.

1260
00:54:17,930 --> 00:54:20,030
The point is, it's spreading incredibly fast.

1261
00:54:20,030 --> 00:54:22,539
I mean, after 24 hours,

1262
00:54:22,539 --> 00:54:24,459
that ship has probably sailed long ago.

1263
00:54:24,459 --> 00:54:28,780
It's very simple, because of the people we have working on development and using it right next to us.

1264
00:54:28,780 --> 00:54:31,220
We all know it's definitely not a person.

1265
00:54:31,220 --> 00:54:33,120
To be honest, it's the same for that robot.

1266
00:54:33,120 --> 00:54:34,720
Its thermal management is problematic.

1267
00:54:34,720 --> 00:54:35,920
Yeah, it gets really hot.

1268
00:54:38,580 --> 00:54:41,010
But it's just one milestone for us. We actually know the future versions will be much better.

1269
00:54:45,950 --> 00:54:49,050
Because many people internally felt that it was better left unsaid.

1270
00:54:49,050 --> 00:54:50,950
Because we knew ourselves.

1271
00:54:50,950 --> 00:54:53,750
But the reality is, for 99.99% of people in this world,

1272
00:54:53,750 --> 00:54:55,810
have no way of connecting with it.

1273
00:54:55,810 --> 00:54:58,470
I remember that night, I was the one who called our team.

1274
00:54:58,470 --> 00:55:01,090
I told them, 'By tomorrow morning, I want you to come up with an idea for me.'

1275
00:55:01,090 --> 00:55:02,730
I'm going to tell everyone,

1276
00:55:02,730 --> 00:55:04,730
This is an actual physical robot.

1277
00:55:04,730 --> 00:55:06,650
and not just a person hiding inside it.

1278
00:55:06,650 --> 00:55:08,300
I forced them to show themselves.

1279
00:55:08,300 --> 00:55:10,840
We had to add something to the agenda at the last minute that morning.

1280
00:55:10,840 --> 00:55:14,609
And after that, it actually happened. Some people started to believe.

1281
00:55:14,609 --> 00:55:16,129
But even more people, on the other hand, didn't believe it.

1282
00:55:16,129 --> 00:55:17,890
So afterwards, we decided to do it again.

1283
00:55:17,890 --> 00:55:19,450
But it happened incredibly fast.

1284
00:55:19,450 --> 00:55:20,910
So why did you choose to handle it this way?

1285
00:55:20,910 --> 00:55:22,830
Because there are so many people online,

1286
00:55:22,830 --> 00:55:24,190
and they're saying all sorts of things,

1287
00:55:24,190 --> 00:55:24,830
If you're A,

1288
00:55:24,830 --> 00:55:27,510
you must be a real person for this reason.

1289
00:55:27,510 --> 00:55:28,910
and if you're B, it might be for that reason instead.

1290
00:55:28,910 --> 00:55:32,180
We figured the easiest part to tackle would be its legs,

1291
00:55:32,180 --> 00:55:33,820
And it's the left leg, specifically.

1292
00:55:33,820 --> 00:55:35,820
Because the left leg is what everyone can see.

1293
00:55:35,820 --> 00:55:40,240
Because, you know, it's walking from left to right.

1294
00:55:40,240 --> 00:55:41,660
The left leg is the one that's most visible.

1295
00:55:41,660 --> 00:55:44,360
So, this is a real robot.

1296
00:55:44,360 --> 00:55:46,120
So, that's why we made the move we did at the time.

1297
00:55:46,120 --> 00:55:48,920
So, what signal did the huge public outcry last year send you?

1298
00:55:48,920 --> 00:55:50,779
When it comes to the R&D of robots,

1299
00:55:50,779 --> 00:55:53,039
I think there were some really interesting outcomes.

1300
00:55:53,039 --> 00:55:56,639
So we went and looked at a lot of Chinese social media.

1301
00:55:56,639 --> 00:56:00,520
how they perceive the value of this robot

1302
00:56:01,840 --> 00:56:06,150
The vast majority of young people hope it will one day be in their homes, helping them with chores.

1303
00:56:06,150 --> 00:56:10,310
But for the people I know, the ones who don't post on social media...

1304
00:56:10,310 --> 00:56:14,650
Men and women who are middle-aged and older.

1305
00:56:14,650 --> 00:56:17,580
You know, people around my age, or even older than me.

1306
00:56:17,580 --> 00:56:20,980
A lot of people are thinking about when they get older,

1307
00:56:20,980 --> 00:56:22,260
So, what's this robot for?

1308
00:56:22,260 --> 00:56:24,180
I think it's a whole different ball game.

1309
00:56:24,180 --> 00:56:26,220
It's just that, in the past, we never really considered things from such a major perspective shift.

1310
00:56:26,220 --> 00:56:28,790
It doesn't have this much data.

1311
00:56:28,790 --> 00:56:32,890
I think it's all a matter of looking at things from a different perspective.

1312
00:56:32,890 --> 00:56:36,160
Right, so did that change the direction or the development process for your robot?

1313
00:56:36,160 --> 00:56:37,740
I think it actually accelerated things.

1314
00:56:37,740 --> 00:56:39,560
In fact, within the robotics industry...

1315
00:56:39,560 --> 00:56:42,230
.a lot of really outstanding people have joined XPeng.

1316
00:56:42,230 --> 00:56:43,470
the auto industry.

1317
00:56:43,470 --> 00:56:47,890
Robots… there's a huge, huge difference between starting a company in robotics compared to the auto industry.

1318
00:56:47,890 --> 00:56:49,750
I can't share that with you just yet.

1319
00:56:49,750 --> 00:56:51,190
I think in about three or four years,

1320
00:56:51,190 --> 00:56:54,280
After a lot of companies have already made those mistakes,

1321
00:56:54,280 --> 00:56:56,420
And that's when you'll see what the real differences are.

1322
00:56:56,420 --> 00:56:58,480
I think it's just that, in another three to four years,

1323
00:56:58,480 --> 00:57:00,160
you're going to see the competition in robotics.

1324
00:57:00,160 --> 00:57:02,100
So what kind of situation will we find ourselves in?

1325
00:57:02,100 --> 00:57:04,720
Xpeng's robot project has run into so, so many pitfalls.

1326
00:57:04,720 --> 00:57:06,840
It's not something you can avoid just by understanding it.

1327
00:57:06,840 --> 00:57:08,380
It’s only after you actually step into it,

1328
00:57:08,380 --> 00:57:10,300
that's when you finally grasp its entire logic.

1329
00:57:10,300 --> 00:57:11,440
So, when it comes to starting a robotics company...

1330
00:57:11,440 --> 00:57:15,859
In fact, I'd even say it's far more difficult than starting a car company.

1331
00:57:15,859 --> 00:57:17,399
And let me tell you, starting a car company is already incredibly difficult.

1332
00:57:17,399 --> 00:57:18,659
From my personal perspective,

1333
00:57:18,659 --> 00:57:19,459
starting a robotics company

1334
00:57:19,459 --> 00:57:22,920
is probably 20 to 100 times harder than starting a car company.

1335
00:57:22,920 --> 00:57:25,240
And look, I'm even setting a low bar here at '20 times' harder.

1336
00:57:25,240 --> 00:57:29,490
So, my own take on this is that, even for a company with Xpeng's capabilities,

1337
00:57:29,490 --> 00:57:32,850
After that robotics marketing push at the end of last year,

1338
00:57:32,850 --> 00:57:35,570
I feel like it all gives us a slightly better shot at success.

1339
00:57:35,570 --> 00:57:37,010
I think it's actually a great thing.

1340
00:57:37,010 --> 00:57:37,750
and valuable.

1341
00:57:37,750 --> 00:57:42,289
So, I really want to emphasize the challenges of this for every company.

1342
00:57:42,289 --> 00:57:44,569
It's a fascinating situation, including for us.

1343
00:57:44,569 --> 00:57:46,500
but it's also a huge undertaking.

1344
00:57:46,500 --> 00:57:48,060
There are just so many robotics companies now.

1345
00:57:48,060 --> 00:57:51,590
I think it's way more than when you guys were getting into car manufacturing.

1346
00:57:51,590 --> 00:57:52,770
newly founded car companies.

1347
00:57:52,770 --> 00:57:55,290
What do you think? In terms of numbers, were there any stats back when you started making cars?

1348
00:57:55,290 --> 00:57:56,870
At its peak, there were over 300 of them.

1349
00:57:56,870 --> 00:58:01,940
But my own feeling is that it was more like a hundred or so.

1350
00:58:01,940 --> 00:58:04,080
But I guess many of them probably died before they could even get off the ground.

1351
00:58:04,080 --> 00:58:05,200
I suspect...

1352
00:58:05,200 --> 00:58:08,140
I think when it comes to robotics companies, I've heard that there are already over 200 of them established.

1353
00:58:08,140 --> 00:58:10,820
In fact, that number is probably double what we saw with car companies back in the day.

1354
00:58:10,820 --> 00:58:12,660
But I still want to say this for myself.

1355
00:58:12,660 --> 00:58:13,950
Robots are a different beast from cars.

1356
00:58:13,950 --> 00:58:17,450
Because within the automotive industry, you might have categories like passenger vehicles.

1357
00:58:17,450 --> 00:58:19,210
Take new energy vehicles, for example.

1358
00:58:19,210 --> 00:58:22,360
commercial vehicles, special-purpose vehicles, or microcars.

1359
00:58:22,360 --> 00:58:23,640
See? That's a category, right?

1360
00:58:23,640 --> 00:58:26,000
But I think when it comes to robots, there are far more than just seven or eight categories.

1361
00:58:26,000 --> 00:58:29,920
Robots could have countless categories.

1362
00:58:29,920 --> 00:58:32,020
For example, you've got robots for the medical field.

1363
00:58:32,020 --> 00:58:35,980
Right, within the robotics ecosystem, you have robots specifically for freight transport.

1364
00:58:35,980 --> 00:58:37,340
or robots for cargo inspection.

1365
00:58:37,340 --> 00:58:38,580
I think all of those are possibilities.

1366
00:58:38,580 --> 00:58:41,100
And there's a really interesting aspect to how we think about robots.

1367
00:58:41,100 --> 00:58:44,590
I believe there are many types of robots, and they don't all have to be humanoid.

1368
00:58:44,590 --> 00:58:46,210
I totally agree with that.

1369
00:58:46,210 --> 00:58:50,030
It's just that we've chosen to pursue the most human-like humanoid robot.

1370
00:58:50,030 --> 00:58:51,640
So, we've chosen this particular path.

1371
00:58:51,640 --> 00:58:53,200
So, on this path,

1372
00:58:53,200 --> 00:58:54,780
and at XPeng, this is the path we're taking.

1373
00:58:54,780 --> 00:58:56,320
but there are many paths to take.

1374
00:58:56,320 --> 00:58:59,540
I believe we can also achieve differentiation and commercialization.

1375
00:58:59,540 --> 00:59:01,430
So, let's look at it from another angle.

1376
00:59:01,430 --> 00:59:03,550
I think for today's robotics companies,

1377
00:59:03,550 --> 00:59:06,680
Personally, I think if you're going down the path of general-purpose humanoid robots,

1378
00:59:06,920 --> 00:59:09,270
99.99% of them will fail.

1379
00:59:09,590 --> 00:59:11,750
But for those pursuing diverse, specialized robots...

1380
00:59:11,750 --> 00:59:14,750
I feel that in this world, there are probably many different solutions.

1381
00:59:14,750 --> 00:59:16,070
So, the chances of success with robots are actually pretty high.

1382
00:59:16,070 --> 00:59:18,340
I think it's higher than for passenger cars.

1383
00:59:18,340 --> 00:59:19,540
That's my take on it.

1384
00:59:19,540 --> 00:59:22,480
So why did you choose the hardest possible path?

1385
00:59:22,480 --> 00:59:23,820
What do you want to do?

1386
00:59:23,820 --> 00:59:25,200
What are you capable of doing?

1387
00:59:25,200 --> 00:59:26,660
And what do you think about whether you should do it or not?

1388
00:59:26,660 --> 00:59:28,340
And then, what you won't do.

1389
00:59:28,340 --> 00:59:31,920
and how you can maximize your chances of success, based on probability.

1390
00:59:31,920 --> 00:59:33,520
You combine these five capabilities,

1391
00:59:33,520 --> 00:59:35,580
Isn't that just your corporate or product strategy?

1392
00:59:35,580 --> 00:59:36,120
So in your view,

1393
00:59:36,120 --> 00:59:38,000
When it comes to general-purpose humanoid robots, who are your competitors?

1394
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:40,080
I don't think there are any competitors for general-purpose humanoid robots right now.

1395
00:59:40,080 --> 00:59:41,480
Everything is developed in-house.

1396
00:59:41,480 --> 00:59:43,890
Because every company that's building robots,

1397
00:59:43,890 --> 00:59:46,430
The most important thing is to build the strongest capabilities you can.

1398
00:59:46,430 --> 00:59:48,650
At the very foundation of your own capabilities is your organization.

1399
00:59:48,650 --> 00:59:50,070
And beyond that is your infrastructure.

1400
00:59:50,070 --> 00:59:53,150
And then, building on that, your entire system architecture.

1401
00:59:53,150 --> 00:59:56,010
This encompasses our systematic capabilities in technology, product, and bringing them to market.

1402
00:59:56,010 --> 00:59:57,700
And then, above that, our own engineering.

1403
00:59:57,700 --> 01:00:00,420
I think one of the key reasons your robot made such a huge splash last year

1404
01:00:00,420 --> 01:00:02,670
It's because it's incredibly lifelike.

1405
01:00:02,670 --> 01:00:04,910
So, what do you think are the most crucial technical bets behind this?

1406
01:00:04,910 --> 01:00:05,310
Yeah...

1407
01:00:05,310 --> 01:00:06,950
And when was it done?

1408
01:00:06,950 --> 01:00:08,710
Yeah, I can talk a little bit about that.

1409
01:00:08,710 --> 01:00:09,710
For example,

1410
01:00:09,710 --> 01:00:12,030
I think the vast majority of people have underestimated this.

1411
01:00:12,030 --> 01:00:13,950
in the motion control of robots.

1412
01:00:13,950 --> 01:00:15,470
In fact, if you look at the automotive industry,

1413
01:00:15,470 --> 01:00:19,320
Motion control is something that, for the past one hundred-plus years, a lot of people...

1414
01:00:19,320 --> 01:00:20,600
thought was already a solved problem.

1415
01:00:20,600 --> 01:00:23,620
So, a lot of passenger car companies, when they build cars...

1416
01:00:23,620 --> 01:00:27,770
They would just buy their motion control capabilities from someone else.

1417
01:00:27,770 --> 01:00:29,050
and then combine and integrate them.

1418
01:00:29,050 --> 01:00:30,850
The very foundation.

1419
01:00:30,850 --> 01:00:34,650
When it comes to robots, their origin story might be traced back to 2018.

1420
01:00:34,650 --> 01:00:36,390
certain open-source motion control frameworks

1421
01:00:36,390 --> 01:00:38,410
and things of that nature.

1422
01:00:38,410 --> 01:00:40,990
So that's why they seem to have so much in common.

1423
01:00:40,990 --> 01:00:44,430
I think that for a robot to be truly well-made in the end,

1424
01:00:44,430 --> 01:00:50,340
It should be able to perform at a level completely beyond what even the next-next generation of cars can achieve.

1425
01:00:50,340 --> 01:00:55,019
Because a car, in reality, is made up of different control domains.

1426
01:00:55,019 --> 01:00:55,879
to handle single-point controls.

1427
01:00:55,879 --> 01:00:59,060
Overall, it's not fully integrated or协同.

1428
01:00:59,060 --> 01:01:02,360
It's just that it's extremely good at defining those boundaries.

1429
01:01:02,360 --> 01:01:04,260
So it's good at dividing up the labor clearly.

1430
01:01:04,260 --> 01:01:05,140
You do A, I'll do B.

1431
01:01:05,140 --> 01:01:07,020
There's a clear boundary between the two of us.

1432
01:01:07,020 --> 01:01:09,860
But in reality, let me give you an example.

1433
01:01:09,860 --> 01:01:15,130
Let's say you have a self-driving car, and its left tire is on snow,

1434
01:01:15,130 --> 01:01:18,670
while the right tire is on grass.

1435
01:01:18,670 --> 01:01:26,040
How do you make a 47.5-degree turn?

1436
01:01:26,040 --> 01:01:27,560
That's a tough one even for a human.

1437
01:01:27,560 --> 01:01:29,080
Because your left side is on snow.

1438
01:01:29,080 --> 01:01:31,720
and on the right, you've got the grip from the grass.

1439
01:01:31,720 --> 01:01:33,280
your overall control over all four wheels,

1440
01:01:33,280 --> 01:01:34,500
the overall balance of the vehicle's motion,

1441
01:01:34,500 --> 01:01:36,000
the management of the entire system's latency,

1442
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:38,600
Let's say you're turning, and there's a car right in front of you.

1443
01:01:38,600 --> 01:01:43,300
or there's someone on the left, it's incredibly easy for the car to lose traction and just rear-end the car in front.

1444
01:01:43,700 --> 01:01:45,640
So, when it comes to a car's motion control today,

1445
01:01:45,640 --> 01:01:48,340
What I want to say is, it's actually very good.

1446
01:01:48,340 --> 01:01:52,250
But it's far, far from being truly versatile.

1447
01:01:52,250 --> 01:01:53,990
So, there's still a huge amount of room for improvement.

1448
01:01:53,990 --> 01:01:55,330
And if we're talking about robots...

1449
01:01:55,330 --> 01:01:56,939
Robots are probably still at a stage where...

1450
01:01:56,939 --> 01:01:59,779
I can't even tell what era of car this is, like from the 1900s or something.

1451
01:01:59,779 --> 01:02:00,919
Maybe the 1930s.

1452
01:02:00,919 --> 01:02:02,419
or cars from the 1920s.

1453
01:02:02,419 --> 01:02:05,490
Maybe, back in those days, you know, the era of the Model T.

1454
01:02:05,490 --> 01:02:07,510
So, have we gotten to the Model T stage yet?

1455
01:02:07,510 --> 01:02:08,730
I think when it comes to robots, we're definitely not at the Model T stage yet.

1456
01:02:08,730 --> 01:02:11,730
I don't think we've seen the equivalent of the Model T in the world of robots yet.

1457
01:02:11,730 --> 01:02:15,090
But I'm just speaking from the perspective of chassis motion control.

1458
01:02:15,090 --> 01:02:16,330
Perhaps it still belongs to that generation.

1459
01:02:16,330 --> 01:02:17,410
So, to get back to your question...

1460
01:02:17,410 --> 01:02:22,850
I think it has to be fully anthropomorphic with all possible postures.

1461
01:02:23,850 --> 01:02:28,350
Achieving motion control through a fully AI-powered combination of movements is incredibly difficult.

1462
01:02:28,350 --> 01:02:29,950
So, for example...

1463
01:02:29,950 --> 01:02:31,590
All the robots you see today,

1464
01:02:31,590 --> 01:02:32,890
Either they are walking,

1465
01:02:32,890 --> 01:02:34,460
or they're fighting.

1466
01:02:34,460 --> 01:02:37,280
Its two types of motion control might just need some tuning.

1467
01:02:37,280 --> 01:02:41,670
So, you might say, 'Okay, we need five types of motion control,' and that's it.

1468
01:02:41,670 --> 01:02:44,070
Actually, for a human being...

1469
01:02:44,070 --> 01:02:46,069
A person has over 200 different joints.

1470
01:02:46,069 --> 01:02:48,189
The combinations are virtually endless.

1471
01:02:48,189 --> 01:02:50,399
It's like right now, I'm just these two fists.

1472
01:02:50,399 --> 01:02:52,599
And on top of that, it's got all these different facial expressions.

1473
01:02:52,599 --> 01:02:56,899
the coordination of your hands, eyes, and feet with your soul and emotions.

1474
01:02:56,899 --> 01:02:59,630
So, the way I see it is...

1475
01:02:59,630 --> 01:03:02,190
So, when it comes to the field of motion control,

1476
01:03:02,190 --> 01:03:10,130
We really hope that it can think like a human, to see how all its movements can be controlled by AI.

1477
01:03:10,130 --> 01:03:11,410
rather than through software control.

1478
01:03:11,410 --> 01:03:15,930
And how do you achieve balance with this control?

1479
01:03:15,930 --> 01:03:17,550
It’s just like a human’s instinct.

1480
01:03:17,550 --> 01:03:19,050
When a person learns to walk,

1481
01:03:19,050 --> 01:03:20,230
and learns to run,

1482
01:03:20,230 --> 01:03:22,230
It has that instinctual ability.

1483
01:03:22,230 --> 01:03:23,650
When it sees a surface,

1484
01:03:23,650 --> 01:03:27,420
Maybe it's a patch of snow, or even grass.

1485
01:03:27,420 --> 01:03:29,460
It might even take a tentative step to test it out.

1486
01:03:29,460 --> 01:03:33,800
to get a feel for the friction and the overall physical sensations.

1487
01:03:33,800 --> 01:03:37,510
Or maybe it's two patches of ground, one with boiling water, and the other with ice-cold water.

1488
01:03:37,510 --> 01:03:38,610
and it's moving with both feet at the same time.

1489
01:03:38,610 --> 01:03:39,750
So, when it comes to the robotics field,

1490
01:03:39,750 --> 01:03:42,830
So, you have to account for all these different scenarios and really think through them.

1491
01:03:42,830 --> 01:03:44,340
to think about motion control.

1492
01:03:44,340 --> 01:03:46,830
So, the way I see it is actually...

1493
01:03:46,830 --> 01:03:51,610
XPeng's potential motion control might be something like the generation after next for our cars.

1494
01:03:51,610 --> 01:03:53,470
So, in a way, from a certain perspective,

1495
01:03:53,470 --> 01:03:55,890
So, why do we think that for the vast majority of robots...

1496
01:03:55,890 --> 01:04:00,040
it's still based on the motion control systems from cars many years ago.

1497
01:04:00,040 --> 01:04:04,510
So naturally, they can only rely on software to stitch it all together.

1498
01:04:04,510 --> 01:04:08,310
So naturally, it's very difficult for them to develop truly comprehensive robotic capabilities.

1499
01:04:08,310 --> 01:04:10,530
So, what do robots mean for XPeng?

1500
01:04:10,530 --> 01:04:11,890
It represents XPeng's long-term vision.

1501
01:04:11,890 --> 01:04:13,210
We don't see it that way.

1502
01:04:13,210 --> 01:04:16,170
We believe that for XPeng, the next decade has three growth curves.

1503
01:04:16,170 --> 01:04:17,680
The first curve is for automobiles.

1504
01:04:17,680 --> 01:04:20,720
to evolve cars into fully-fledged intelligent agents.

1505
01:04:20,720 --> 01:04:23,180
The second, I believe, is robots.

1506
01:04:23,180 --> 01:04:25,360
I think robots are, by their very nature, intelligent agents.

1507
01:04:25,360 --> 01:04:26,940
In reality, cars still have to prove themselves.

1508
01:04:26,940 --> 01:04:30,760
It also takes a decade to prove that software capabilities account for 50% of the value.

1509
01:04:30,760 --> 01:04:33,149
But I don't think robots need to prove that.

1510
01:04:33,509 --> 01:04:35,429
If a robot has really bad software capabilities,

1511
01:04:35,429 --> 01:04:36,649
You basically wouldn't want it.

1512
01:04:36,649 --> 01:04:37,829
And of course, if its hardware is terrible,

1513
01:04:37,829 --> 01:04:41,770
you wouldn't use it either. I think, for this third growth curve, we see it as globalization.

1514
01:04:41,770 --> 01:04:44,470
Actually, there's one major difference between robots and cars.

1515
01:04:44,470 --> 01:04:46,530
And this is something that most people have overlooked.

1516
01:04:46,530 --> 01:04:50,010
What I mean is, once robots are ready for mass production,

1517
01:04:50,010 --> 01:04:53,310
the speed at which they scale will far surpass that of cars.

1518
01:04:53,310 --> 01:04:54,790
Take cars, for example. Over the past 100-plus years,

1519
01:04:54,790 --> 01:04:55,990
expanded incrementally.

1520
01:04:55,990 --> 01:04:57,810
For one, you need to build roads.

1521
01:04:57,810 --> 01:04:59,770
Second, traffic laws and regulations had to be established.

1522
01:04:59,770 --> 01:05:02,870
Second, the difficulty of mass production is extremely high.

1523
01:05:02,870 --> 01:05:05,270
For example, let's say you make a really great car today.

1524
01:05:05,270 --> 01:05:07,360
and sell 100,000 units in a single day.

1525
01:05:07,360 --> 01:05:07,760
But sorry,

1526
01:05:07,760 --> 01:05:10,980
You don't have the capacity to build 100,000 cars the very next month.

1527
01:05:10,980 --> 01:05:13,380
Besides, you wouldn't dare to do that three months down the line either.

1528
01:05:13,380 --> 01:05:14,660
say you actually manage to build 100,000 units in a month,

1529
01:05:14,660 --> 01:05:17,400
Because you have no idea if you can actually sell those 100,000 units later on.

1530
01:05:17,400 --> 01:05:20,000
That's just the nature of the auto industry.

1531
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:21,520
But I think robots are a different story.

1532
01:05:21,520 --> 01:05:23,489
Robots have the potential to be exceptionally good.

1533
01:05:23,489 --> 01:05:25,609
at a single point. And remember, it's one specific point.

1534
01:05:25,609 --> 01:05:26,349
Not a broad area,

1535
01:05:26,349 --> 01:05:30,300
I think it has the potential to create a massive, explosive effect.

1536
01:05:30,300 --> 01:05:33,220
It's like how I think the biggest thing in digital AI last year...

1537
01:05:33,220 --> 01:05:35,280
I mean, Anthropic's coding, for example.

1538
01:05:35,280 --> 01:05:36,700
in a very short amount of time,

1539
01:05:36,700 --> 01:05:39,080
So, in less than 18 months, basically.

1540
01:05:39,080 --> 01:05:43,300
From the second half of the year before last to the end of last year, there was a massive change.

1541
01:05:43,300 --> 01:05:45,870
Personally, I believe robotics also holds a lot of promise.

1542
01:05:45,870 --> 01:05:46,870
It'll be slower, yes.

1543
01:05:46,870 --> 01:05:48,990
Because that's still a digital world.

1544
01:05:48,990 --> 01:05:50,110
and a physical one, but the potential is still there.

1545
01:05:50,110 --> 01:05:52,080
So, will it be even slower than the car industry?

1546
01:05:52,080 --> 01:05:56,140
Well, I think if a robot's software capabilities can reach a certain level,

1547
01:05:56,140 --> 01:05:58,880
in terms of hardware speed, it will be far faster than a car.

1548
01:05:58,880 --> 01:06:00,080
Of course, on the other hand...

1549
01:06:00,080 --> 01:06:01,460
Because, you know, XPeng is an automotive manufacturer.

1550
01:06:01,460 --> 01:06:03,520
Now, when it comes to us making robots versus many other companies...

1551
01:06:03,520 --> 01:06:06,470
We develop 80% of our hardware in-house.

1552
01:06:06,470 --> 01:06:09,290
We handle the chips, the joints...

1553
01:06:09,290 --> 01:06:09,990
Right.

1554
01:06:09,990 --> 01:06:11,810
We develop everything in-house.

1555
01:06:11,810 --> 01:06:14,770
It's just that, when it comes to collaboration, we might partner with various companies.

1556
01:06:14,770 --> 01:06:17,490
For a Tier 1 supplier, we might work with their upstream partners, the Tier 2s.

1557
01:06:17,490 --> 01:06:18,510
we work with the Tier 2 suppliers.

1558
01:06:18,510 --> 01:06:21,880
This is the only way you can get the quality and scale right.

1559
01:06:21,880 --> 01:06:23,900
So, are you planning to start mass production in the second half of this year?

1560
01:06:23,900 --> 01:06:25,290
So what do you see as the main challenges right now?

1561
01:06:25,290 --> 01:06:27,490
I think there are quite a few points, actually.

1562
01:06:27,490 --> 01:06:30,050
First, can we make the hardware reliable and stable enough?

1563
01:06:30,050 --> 01:06:34,360
I think the second challenge is dealing with high-level, multiple large models.

1564
01:06:34,360 --> 01:06:37,520
And whether they can be effectively integrated.

1565
01:06:37,520 --> 01:06:40,200
And I think the third challenge, which is actually a really tough one, is whether we can prove the commercial viability.

1566
01:06:40,200 --> 01:06:41,830
Ah...

1567
01:06:41,830 --> 01:06:43,730
In reality, robotics is just a minefield of problems.

1568
01:06:43,730 --> 01:06:45,750
And that's why I say it's so much harder than making cars.

1569
01:06:45,750 --> 01:06:46,950
With cars, once you've built one,

1570
01:06:46,950 --> 01:06:47,950
Let's say there's no competition,

1571
01:06:47,950 --> 01:06:49,170
and let's say there are customers who need it,

1572
01:06:49,170 --> 01:06:51,870
you can be certain that it's something you can sell.

1573
01:06:51,870 --> 01:06:53,930
But when it comes to robots, you can't say that.

1574
01:06:53,930 --> 01:06:55,450
Even to this day, the definition of a robot hasn't been clearly established.

1575
01:06:55,450 --> 01:06:57,130
The market is waiting, too.

1576
01:06:57,130 --> 01:06:57,930
What the market is waiting for is to see if you have something like...

1577
01:06:57,930 --> 01:06:59,990
Yeah.

1578
01:06:59,990 --> 01:07:03,250
or maybe, a phone like the iPhone 4 to come along.

1579
01:07:03,250 --> 01:07:09,070
But I believe that the first commercially mass-produced robot,

1580
01:07:09,980 --> 01:07:12,700
I don't think we've even reached the iPhone 1 stage yet.

1581
01:07:13,740 --> 01:07:17,330
But the iPhone 1, at the end of the day, was just a tool.

1582
01:07:17,690 --> 01:07:22,170
It could be replaced, because back in those days, there were many other mobile devices.

1583
01:07:22,170 --> 01:07:24,150
There was Nokia, there was Motorola.

1584
01:07:24,150 --> 01:07:25,530
Sony Ericsson, you name it.

1585
01:07:25,530 --> 01:07:27,240
But when it comes to robots, when they finally emerge,

1586
01:07:27,240 --> 01:07:29,200
A lot of people haven't managed to pull off anything similar.

1587
01:07:29,200 --> 01:07:32,080
So I think, again, it's not really a comparable situation.

1588
01:07:32,080 --> 01:07:33,360
So, what do you think your odds of success are?

1589
01:07:33,360 --> 01:07:35,440
In a battle that's going to take so long...

1590
01:07:35,440 --> 01:07:37,400
Well, that depends on how big you set your sights.

1591
01:07:37,400 --> 01:07:39,780
and then you'll know what your chances of winning are.

1592
01:07:39,780 --> 01:07:42,840
I think that, in my opinion...

1593
01:07:42,840 --> 01:07:47,990
we're probably looking at about a 20% chance of success.

1594
01:07:47,990 --> 01:07:50,410
And I think, for a Chinese company, that's the highest I've seen.

1595
01:07:50,410 --> 01:07:52,250
And I believe that's the highest success rate I've seen.

1596
01:07:52,250 --> 01:07:53,990
But just two years ago, you were telling me...

1597
01:07:53,990 --> 01:07:56,090
Building cars is like swimming in a sea of blood.

1598
01:07:56,090 --> 01:07:57,050
So, what about making robots?

1599
01:07:57,050 --> 01:07:58,370
We haven't entered the red ocean yet.

1600
01:07:58,370 --> 01:07:59,460
The sea of blood is still ahead of us.

1601
01:07:59,460 --> 01:08:01,740
But I think there's a fundamental difference with robotics.

1602
01:08:01,740 --> 01:08:05,420
The thing is, the AI component in robots is incredibly powerful.

1603
01:08:05,420 --> 01:08:08,480
But for the group that was originally swimming in that sea of blood...

1604
01:08:08,480 --> 01:08:10,320
the people you're swimming with

1605
01:08:10,320 --> 01:08:12,900
The truth is, the vast majority of people don't really understand AI.

1606
01:08:12,900 --> 01:08:14,660
You know, a lot of people in the auto industry today...

1607
01:08:14,660 --> 01:08:16,640
claiming it's because I don't know software.

1608
01:08:16,640 --> 01:08:18,560
So I'll just find a good Tier 1 supplier.

1609
01:08:18,560 --> 01:08:22,150
But that same approach just doesn't work in the world of robotics.

1610
01:08:22,150 --> 01:08:26,350
So, the bloodbath in the robotics industry is just like the dot-com competition back in the day.

1611
01:08:26,350 --> 01:08:29,440
It will quickly shift from a red ocean to a blue ocean.

1612
01:08:29,440 --> 01:08:32,160
So it's going to progress at an incredibly fast pace.

1613
01:08:32,160 --> 01:08:33,600
Alright, so we were just talking about robots.

1614
01:08:33,600 --> 01:08:35,480
So, you're also launching several new cars this year, right?

1615
01:08:35,480 --> 01:08:37,120
Including your GX.

1616
01:08:37,120 --> 01:08:38,780
So, why don't we talk about your product?

1617
01:08:38,780 --> 01:08:42,430
Right. The GX is XPeng's return to the high-end market.

1618
01:08:42,430 --> 01:08:48,459
Right, and this is also the first time we've made a full-size, six-seater luxury SUV.

1619
01:08:48,459 --> 01:08:50,519
So, it's our flagship, our flagship SUV.

1620
01:08:50,519 --> 01:08:51,339
It's very interesting this year at the Beijing Auto Show.

1621
01:08:51,339 --> 01:08:55,309
There were about 30 such all-new, full-size models.

1622
01:08:55,309 --> 01:08:57,309
Uh,

1623
01:08:57,309 --> 01:09:00,289
There are a few models that come to mind.

1624
01:09:00,289 --> 01:09:01,949
In fact, XPeng has been doing a lot in this area.

1625
01:09:01,949 --> 01:09:04,360
and how we differ from them.

1626
01:09:04,360 --> 01:09:07,960
For the first time, we are pondering...

1627
01:09:07,960 --> 01:09:10,640
it's about how we take our cars,

1628
01:09:10,640 --> 01:09:12,380
a lot of the capabilities from our flying cars and robots,

1629
01:09:12,380 --> 01:09:15,800
and in this new generation of smart cars, we've managed to bring them all together.

1630
01:09:15,800 --> 01:09:16,820
Let me give you an example.

1631
01:09:16,820 --> 01:09:20,880
We took the redundant, core flight components from our flying car project,

1632
01:09:20,880 --> 01:09:23,640
and brought them into this car.

1633
01:09:23,640 --> 01:09:27,820
And of course, I believe this GX is the very first of its kind in all of China.

1634
01:09:27,820 --> 01:09:29,560
an automaker has built a factory-integrated Robotaxi.

1635
01:09:29,560 --> 01:09:33,300
So, it has eight layers of full safety redundancy.

1636
01:09:33,300 --> 01:09:35,300
So, let's say you drive it out into the wild,

1637
01:09:35,300 --> 01:09:37,240
If the power source fails, it can still drive.

1638
01:09:37,240 --> 01:09:39,960
If the power source fails, it can still run. Even if a rat...

1639
01:09:39,960 --> 01:09:42,549
Or a rat chews through the wiring harness, and it can still run.

1640
01:09:42,549 --> 01:09:43,729
It's just like an airplane.

1641
01:09:43,729 --> 01:09:45,869
It allows for redundancy.

1642
01:09:45,869 --> 01:09:48,819
And for the second point, let me give you an example.

1643
01:09:48,819 --> 01:09:53,399
We've integrated the car's steer-by-wire chassis with our new EEA architecture,

1644
01:09:53,399 --> 01:09:56,439
and tie it into our VLA autonomous driving system.

1645
01:09:56,439 --> 01:09:58,940
This allows the new chassis

1646
01:09:58,940 --> 01:10:03,580
This can raise the baseline performance during the VLA's execution.

1647
01:10:03,580 --> 01:10:05,360
Which means, it has a higher safety level.

1648
01:10:05,360 --> 01:10:06,540
It has lower latency.

1649
01:10:06,540 --> 01:10:10,220
The responsiveness of the control can be improved by almost, well, several dozen percent.

1650
01:10:10,220 --> 01:10:13,560
So, this is actually an example we're giving.

1651
01:10:13,560 --> 01:10:15,360
Alright, so the third point, which brings us to the present day.

1652
01:10:15,360 --> 01:10:18,440
We're talking about the 'thinking' part inside the robot,

1653
01:10:18,440 --> 01:10:20,340
So, the robot has to receive a task.

1654
01:10:20,340 --> 01:10:22,220
For example, let's say Xiao Jun asks, 'Bring me a bottle of water.'

1655
01:10:22,220 --> 01:10:23,540
So, that's the task.

1656
01:10:23,540 --> 01:10:24,640
First, it has to determine who you are.

1657
01:10:24,640 --> 01:10:25,460
You're not my master.

1658
01:10:25,460 --> 01:10:26,740
I'm not going to listen to you.

1659
01:10:26,740 --> 01:10:27,920
Then it has to figure out where the water is.

1660
01:10:27,920 --> 01:10:29,120
What kind of water would you like?

1661
01:10:29,120 --> 01:10:30,540
And after you get the water, where do you get it from?

1662
01:10:30,540 --> 01:10:32,820
and how I'm going to give it to you... the whole series of steps.

1663
01:10:32,820 --> 01:10:35,440
And we'll see that in cars in the very near future.

1664
01:10:35,440 --> 01:10:38,200
So that's why we haven't really talked much about this publicly yet.

1665
01:10:38,200 --> 01:10:41,150
In fact, it itself is derived from robotics.

1666
01:10:41,150 --> 01:10:44,150
Of course, it also draws on a great deal of our capabilities from the automotive side.

1667
01:10:44,150 --> 01:10:46,310
For example, let's take this car.

1668
01:10:46,310 --> 01:10:49,830
You can fold down the second-row seats completely flat.

1669
01:10:49,830 --> 01:10:51,130
turning it into a two-row vehicle.

1670
01:10:51,130 --> 01:10:52,790
or turn it into a 2.5-row vehicle.

1671
01:10:52,790 --> 01:10:54,150
We call it the four-seater version.

1672
01:10:54,150 --> 01:10:56,310
or a vehicle that can seat five or six people.

1673
01:10:56,310 --> 01:10:59,530
So, what you'll actually see is that it takes a lot of XPeng's own capabilities,

1674
01:10:59,530 --> 01:11:01,980
And marry them with our capabilities in both automobiles and robotics.

1675
01:11:01,980 --> 01:11:05,260
So essentially, it's a really interesting fusion of all these things.

1676
01:11:05,260 --> 01:11:07,460
And on top of that, we've also incorporated a lot from our partners.

1677
01:11:07,460 --> 01:11:10,180
For example, we worked with Fuyao Glass to develop privacy glass.

1678
01:11:10,180 --> 01:11:13,860
We teamed up with Midea to create a new generation of in-car refrigerators.

1679
01:11:13,860 --> 01:11:17,800
I think there are just so many interesting combinations of capabilities.

1680
01:11:17,800 --> 01:11:22,619
So, what we've always believed is that just building something that looks big on the outside...

1681
01:11:24,939 --> 01:11:26,670
Some parts look good,

1682
01:11:26,670 --> 01:11:28,330
The interior is crude,

1683
01:11:28,330 --> 01:11:30,570
and the details aren't user-friendly.

1684
01:11:30,570 --> 01:11:33,030
and it's just a car cobbled together with a bunch of different features.

1685
01:11:33,030 --> 01:11:36,680
I think so. You'd call it a bloodbath.

1686
01:11:36,680 --> 01:11:39,940
And in a way, you're actually seeing a ton of cars like this at the auto shows.

1687
01:11:39,940 --> 01:11:43,359
But how can you possibly do something different?

1688
01:11:43,359 --> 01:11:46,039
It demands a comprehensive, all-encompassing approach.

1689
01:11:46,039 --> 01:11:49,830
For each area, some might say, 'Alright, I'll score a 60 in this one.'

1690
01:11:49,830 --> 01:11:50,670
another is an 80,

1691
01:11:50,670 --> 01:11:51,730
And another one at 85.

1692
01:11:51,730 --> 01:11:54,139
your worst score might still be an 80.

1693
01:11:54,139 --> 01:11:57,019
And on top of that, you have even more areas scoring 90 and 95.

1694
01:11:57,019 --> 01:12:00,120
Only then can you possibly come out on top in this war.

1695
01:12:00,120 --> 01:12:02,380
So, this is a really fascinating thing.

1696
01:12:02,380 --> 01:12:03,680
So, how was this price determined?

1697
01:12:03,680 --> 01:12:04,520
Did you have it all figured out from the very beginning?

1698
01:12:04,520 --> 01:12:05,500
Or was it decided at the end?

1699
01:12:05,500 --> 01:12:09,100
No car has ever had a perfectly clear logic figured out right from the start.

1700
01:12:09,100 --> 01:12:10,600
It all comes down to a plan.

1701
01:12:10,600 --> 01:12:13,740
This plan depends on which market you're trying to capture.

1702
01:12:13,740 --> 01:12:16,550
What size do you expect this market to be?

1703
01:12:16,550 --> 01:12:17,790
What kind of profit margins you're expecting.

1704
01:12:17,790 --> 01:12:19,670
And also, within this market...

1705
01:12:19,670 --> 01:12:22,860
And what kind of players might we see in the market?

1706
01:12:22,860 --> 01:12:24,440
I think there are a few main points to cover.

1707
01:12:24,440 --> 01:12:25,780
And right now, it's in pre-sale.

1708
01:12:25,780 --> 01:12:27,900
It should be on May 21st.

1709
01:12:27,900 --> 01:12:29,260
We will be making the official release.

1710
01:12:29,260 --> 01:12:32,540
So, at the launch event, you'll see our more specific configurations and pricing.

1711
01:12:32,540 --> 01:12:36,850
Are you worried about repeating the mistakes of the G9?

1712
01:12:36,850 --> 01:12:40,170
Because the way we thought and our logic back then...

1713
01:12:40,170 --> 01:12:43,390
and the logic we're using now... I think the difference is night and day.

1714
01:12:43,390 --> 01:12:44,910
There's so much more to it.

1715
01:12:44,910 --> 01:12:46,210
Looking at it a few years from now,

1716
01:12:46,210 --> 01:12:48,870
If you can elevate your perspective to a higher level,

1717
01:12:48,870 --> 01:12:52,909
you'll most likely be able to figure out what went wrong in the past,

1718
01:12:52,909 --> 01:12:55,089
and more importantly, you can figure out where the current problems lie.

1719
01:12:55,089 --> 01:12:55,809
I think that's it.

1720
01:12:55,809 --> 01:12:59,260
And getting to where we are today, we're not going to be like we were before.

1721
01:12:59,260 --> 01:13:01,380
In other words, the stronger your systemic capabilities become,

1722
01:13:01,380 --> 01:13:04,719
the harder it is for you to fail easily at just one or two points.

1723
01:13:04,719 --> 01:13:07,079
And you've said personally that you're quite fond of this car too.

1724
01:13:07,079 --> 01:13:09,359
And you've said you want to build a car for your friends.

1725
01:13:09,359 --> 01:13:10,899
So, what kind of people are we talking about here?

1726
01:13:10,899 --> 01:13:12,419
So, who's your target customer profile?

1727
01:13:12,419 --> 01:13:17,440
I'd say they're over 30 and are quite bold.

1728
01:13:18,600 --> 01:13:21,770
And many of them are doing very well for themselves.

1729
01:13:21,970 --> 01:13:24,130
Some are entrepreneurs.

1730
01:13:24,130 --> 01:13:27,190
some are great managers,

1731
01:13:27,190 --> 01:13:28,630
skilled professionals.

1732
01:13:28,630 --> 01:13:31,500
They're willing to explore new technologies,

1733
01:13:31,500 --> 01:13:33,500
and experience the luxury of new technology.

1734
01:13:33,500 --> 01:13:35,300
a mindset that aligns quite well with ours.

1735
01:13:35,300 --> 01:13:37,040
I think he's one of our first users.

1736
01:13:37,040 --> 01:13:38,420
So, for this car of ours...

1737
01:13:38,420 --> 01:13:42,230
We're aiming for a more family-oriented, tech-luxury experience.

1738
01:13:42,230 --> 01:13:44,150
So when you drive it out, what's the feedback from your friends?

1739
01:13:44,150 --> 01:13:46,010
Actually, a lot of my friends really like it.

1740
01:13:46,010 --> 01:13:47,590
I'll be in Beijing tomorrow.

1741
01:13:47,590 --> 01:13:50,610
I have a group of friends who've all made plans to come and check out our car together.

1742
01:13:50,610 --> 01:13:51,790
In fact, a lot of people have told me,

1743
01:13:51,790 --> 01:13:55,590
He was like, 'Xpeng, you guys should've made a car this big a long time ago.'

1744
01:13:55,590 --> 01:14:00,410
He said, 'You know, my family and I, we've been wanting a bigger car for a while now.'

1745
01:14:00,410 --> 01:14:02,630
And some of them might have driven other cars from us in the past.

1746
01:14:02,630 --> 01:14:04,100
while others might have driven other XPeng models.

1747
01:14:04,100 --> 01:14:06,020
In fact, they've all been really looking forward to us having a bigger car.

1748
01:14:06,020 --> 01:14:07,140
and fulfill their needs.

1749
01:14:07,140 --> 01:14:08,700
So how do you handle the competition from Li Auto?

1750
01:14:08,700 --> 01:14:10,790
I think we see every company as a peer and a potential partner.

1751
01:14:10,790 --> 01:14:12,310
and allies as well.

1752
01:14:12,310 --> 01:14:13,870
and competitors, perhaps.

1753
01:14:13,870 --> 01:14:17,230
In fact, I went over to Li Xiang's booth today to check it out.

1754
01:14:17,230 --> 01:14:19,669
And I believe the new L9 is a very impressive vehicle as well.

1755
01:14:19,669 --> 01:14:23,740
Yesterday, I went to Bill Li's place and checked out the ES9.

1756
01:14:26,820 --> 01:14:32,500
I think that for this big 9-series model, NIO, XPeng, and Li Auto will each be bringing their own unique perspectives and approaches to the table.

1757
01:14:32,500 --> 01:14:34,680
So, what have you learned from looking back at the G9?

1758
01:14:34,680 --> 01:14:36,460
And will you be applying those to this generation of cars?

1759
01:14:36,460 --> 01:14:37,600
I think there are way too many things to list.

1760
01:14:37,600 --> 01:14:40,660
Our organization was restructured too.

1761
01:14:40,660 --> 01:14:45,630
We've adjusted our product planning, and our understanding of our customers has changed as well.

1762
01:14:45,630 --> 01:14:47,670
Even our business logic had to be adjusted.

1763
01:14:47,670 --> 01:14:48,730
I think that's a lot.

1764
01:14:48,730 --> 01:14:51,710
Has it really been three and a half years already?

1765
01:14:51,710 --> 01:14:54,060
From the end of 2022 to now,

1766
01:14:54,060 --> 01:14:55,100
I feel like it's been way too much.

1767
01:14:55,100 --> 01:14:55,840
Wow, that's a lot of confidence.

1768
01:14:55,840 --> 01:14:58,600
I think this is a completely different league of capability.

1769
01:14:58,600 --> 01:15:12,590
The automotive industry is an immensely complex, large-scale collective system that intricately weaves together technology, human nature, and business operations.

1770
01:15:12,590 --> 01:15:15,380
And that's why it's called the 'crown jewel of manufacturing'.

1771
01:15:15,380 --> 01:15:19,040
So, the deeper you go into this field,

1772
01:15:19,040 --> 01:15:20,100
and the deeper your understanding becomes,

1773
01:15:20,100 --> 01:15:23,549
you'll start to see things from a whole new perspective.

1774
01:15:23,549 --> 01:15:26,869
In fact, for many smaller pieces of hardware, or consumer-grade hardware,

1775
01:15:26,869 --> 01:15:28,240
that aren't visible to them.

1776
01:15:28,240 --> 01:15:30,520
They've outsourced a lot of their manufacturing.

1777
01:15:30,520 --> 01:15:32,320
They possess immense supply capabilities,

1778
01:15:32,320 --> 01:15:33,260
and rely on their supply chains.

1779
01:15:33,260 --> 01:15:35,129
The possibilities for combination aren't that high.

1780
01:15:35,129 --> 01:15:37,089
So, when it comes to the auto industry,

1781
01:15:37,089 --> 01:15:41,109
So why is it that for the period from 2022 to 2026,

1782
01:15:41,109 --> 01:15:44,579
I personally believe it's a massive, qualitative leap forward.

1783
01:15:44,579 --> 01:15:46,259
If someone says a Xpeng car is ugly,

1784
01:15:46,259 --> 01:15:47,439
What are your thoughts on that?

1785
01:15:47,439 --> 01:15:49,139
People will say that about every car.

1786
01:15:49,139 --> 01:15:51,520
when other people say their cars are ugly.

1787
01:15:51,960 --> 01:15:54,720
Aesthetics is a matter of personal taste.

1788
01:15:54,720 --> 01:15:56,440
So, what do you think? Do XPeng's cars look good?

1789
01:15:56,440 --> 01:15:58,760
I think they're on the right track to becoming more and more beautiful.

1790
01:15:58,760 --> 01:16:00,480
But as for my confidence in other areas, I'm not as sure.

1791
01:16:00,480 --> 01:16:03,040
But when it comes to what's ugly and what's beautiful, I'm actually quite confident.

1792
01:16:03,040 --> 01:16:04,760
You mentioned that looks are number one.

1793
01:16:04,760 --> 01:16:07,800
Internally, what's considered good-looking is all relative.

1794
01:16:07,800 --> 01:16:11,089
Only by being number one in multiple areas can we possibly succeed.

1795
01:16:11,089 --> 01:16:13,530
Looks are one of those areas.

1796
01:16:13,530 --> 01:16:17,190
So why not opt for a strategy of making fewer, more refined car models?

1797
01:16:17,190 --> 01:16:18,770
So why are you rolling out four new car models this year?

1798
01:16:18,770 --> 01:16:20,890
I think every company has its own philosophy.

1799
01:16:21,630 --> 01:16:25,880
You can't go and ask Company A why they don't focus on doing a few things really well.

1800
01:16:25,880 --> 01:16:27,240
or why Company B doesn't go big and wide.

1801
01:16:27,240 --> 01:16:29,580
Each has its own different logic.

1802
01:16:29,580 --> 01:16:31,780
You seem really confident about everything this year.

1803
01:16:31,780 --> 01:16:34,880
I think if you're an entrepreneur, you can't afford not to be confident, right?

1804
01:16:34,880 --> 01:16:37,710
So where are you spending most of your time these days?

1805
01:16:37,710 --> 01:16:38,830
On the cars, on the robots.

1806
01:16:38,830 --> 01:16:39,870
In AI, or...?

1807
01:16:39,870 --> 01:16:41,830
Or is it in organization, or procurement?

1808
01:16:41,830 --> 01:16:43,590
We're involved in everything you've mentioned.

1809
01:16:43,590 --> 01:16:45,870
But I don't think it's any of those. I think the biggest factor...

1810
01:16:45,870 --> 01:16:47,590
I think it really comes down to strategy and planning.

1811
01:16:47,590 --> 01:16:49,300
It's about what the future will be like.

1812
01:16:49,300 --> 01:16:50,880
It's like all the questions you just asked,

1813
01:16:50,880 --> 01:16:52,300
questions like 'who's successful,' and so on.

1814
01:16:52,300 --> 01:16:54,200
Maybe they'll be more successful in the future.

1815
01:16:54,200 --> 01:16:55,760
But from where I'm standing today, I wouldn't call any of that success.

1816
01:16:55,760 --> 01:16:57,470
Uh...

1817
01:16:58,750 --> 01:17:01,010
Take the auto industry, for example. Is scale considered success?

1818
01:17:01,010 --> 01:17:02,530
it's one of the hallmarks of success.

1819
01:17:02,530 --> 01:17:04,130
But not all of them necessarily succeed.

1820
01:17:04,130 --> 01:17:06,530
So, what about profit? Does that count as success?

1821
01:17:06,530 --> 01:17:08,450
Some profits might be temporary.

1822
01:17:08,450 --> 01:17:09,390
and it’s also agonizing.

1823
01:17:09,390 --> 01:17:11,930
So, when it comes to entrepreneurs,

1824
01:17:11,930 --> 01:17:13,090
People have vastly different definitions of success.

1825
01:17:13,090 --> 01:17:14,170
So, looking at it from another angle,

1826
01:17:14,170 --> 01:17:16,460
I think I've probably given it a lot more thought.

1827
01:17:16,460 --> 01:17:21,100
It's a question of the entire enterprise's product and business strategy and planning.

1828
01:17:21,100 --> 01:17:22,340
Ah...

1829
01:17:22,340 --> 01:17:25,840
But for all these planning issues, they all hinge on your technology.

1830
01:17:25,840 --> 01:17:27,260
your organizational issues,

1831
01:17:27,260 --> 01:17:31,790
your entire market-facing issues, and this whole series of combined capabilities.

1832
01:17:31,790 --> 01:17:33,510
and only then can you finally pull it off.

1833
01:17:33,510 --> 01:17:34,390
Something like that.

1834
01:17:34,390 --> 01:17:37,110
So, what would you say was the most important thing for you this year?

1835
01:17:37,110 --> 01:17:38,890
No, they're all important.

1836
01:17:38,890 --> 01:17:40,070
A lot of things are important.

1837
01:17:40,070 --> 01:17:44,080
The thing is, the automotive industry is a really complex problem.

1838
01:17:44,080 --> 01:17:48,620
It's more complex than what a single person or a straightforward company would face.

1839
01:17:48,620 --> 01:17:51,500
He might say, "I just need to get this one thing right, and that's enough."

1840
01:17:51,500 --> 01:17:55,040
Even if you do one thing perfectly in the auto industry, it doesn't mean you can succeed overall.

1841
01:17:55,040 --> 01:17:56,720
And this is a very painful question to tackle.

1842
01:17:56,720 --> 01:18:01,239
Just like the point about your strengths, weaknesses, and breadth of capabilities.

1843
01:18:01,239 --> 01:18:03,919
A lot of people would say, you should just focus on having one major strength.

1844
01:18:03,919 --> 01:18:05,750
And for the most part, that's true.

1845
01:18:05,750 --> 01:18:08,810
But most of the time, the answer to that question, when it comes to the auto industry,

1846
01:18:08,810 --> 01:18:11,110
It's a composite system.

1847
01:18:11,110 --> 01:18:12,570
Just doing one thing well isn't enough.

1848
01:18:12,570 --> 01:18:15,250
For instance, let's say you make autonomous driving exceptionally good.

1849
01:18:15,250 --> 01:18:16,530
So what if you achieve Level 4?

1850
01:18:17,570 --> 01:18:21,130
First of all, my general take is, anyone who claims they can achieve it this year...

1851
01:18:21,130 --> 01:18:22,110
I think that's just bullshit.

1852
01:18:22,110 --> 01:18:24,110
Second, even if they did manage to do it,

1853
01:18:24,110 --> 01:18:26,770
it wouldn't hold that much value for them anyway.

1854
01:18:26,770 --> 01:18:29,610
Because its value is something that's going to be realized gradually over time.

1855
01:18:29,610 --> 01:18:31,770
So, when do you think we'll see Level 4 autonomy become a reality?

1856
01:18:31,770 --> 01:18:35,710
I would put the odds on 18 to 24 months.

1857
01:18:35,710 --> 01:18:37,750
And is this for your company specifically, or for the industry as a whole?

1858
01:18:37,750 --> 01:18:40,430
And for us, what will achieving that bring?

1859
01:18:40,430 --> 01:18:42,380
Will that lead to higher car sales?

1860
01:18:42,380 --> 01:18:46,540
Bigger sales are a 100% given. The only question is, by how much?

1861
01:18:46,540 --> 01:18:48,020
I need verification.

1862
01:18:48,020 --> 01:18:51,020
But even more sales don't necessarily equate to long-term value.

1863
01:18:51,020 --> 01:18:52,540
You see, each of these presents a different set of challenges.

1864
01:18:52,540 --> 01:18:55,210
For example, just last month...

1865
01:18:55,210 --> 01:18:58,370
At the end of March, we released the first version of our second-generation VLA.

1866
01:18:58,370 --> 01:19:02,130
I shared some data with everyone at the auto show recently.

1867
01:19:02,130 --> 01:19:05,150
In April, China's auto sales...

1868
01:19:05,150 --> 01:19:07,270
Both year-over-year and month-over-month, sales were down by about 20%.

1869
01:19:07,270 --> 01:19:11,180
But for us, we saw an increase of about 50% to 70%.

1870
01:19:11,180 --> 01:19:14,500
And a significant portion of that is thanks to our second-generation VLA.

1871
01:19:14,500 --> 01:19:15,360
So, is it any good?

1872
01:19:15,360 --> 01:19:16,180
I think it's pretty good.

1873
01:19:16,180 --> 01:19:18,040
So, what if we achieve L4?

1874
01:19:18,040 --> 01:19:19,820
And to what extent can we improve this capability?

1875
01:19:19,820 --> 01:19:22,800
Twofold? Fivefold? Tenfold?

1876
01:19:22,800 --> 01:19:24,760
I think it's really hard for me to say.

1877
01:19:24,760 --> 01:19:26,160
Is that a good thing or a bad thing?

1878
01:19:26,160 --> 01:19:29,250
Secondly, what will its impact be on society?

1879
01:19:29,250 --> 01:19:30,930
and what kind of impact it will have on the industry.

1880
01:19:30,930 --> 01:19:32,490
The thing is, today we actually have a lot of...

1881
01:19:32,490 --> 01:19:34,150
And opinions on this are quite divided.

1882
01:19:34,150 --> 01:19:35,520
What I really want to say is this:

1883
01:19:35,520 --> 01:19:37,160
The ultimate success of an auto company...

1884
01:19:37,160 --> 01:19:39,820
doesn't just come from a single capability within AI,

1885
01:19:39,820 --> 01:19:43,110
or a single capability in sales.

1886
01:19:43,110 --> 01:19:43,430
Uh...

1887
01:19:43,430 --> 01:19:44,350
I think it's neither of those.

1888
01:19:44,350 --> 01:19:48,410
Professor Yu Kai often says that you are the toughest nut to crack among all his clients.

1889
01:19:48,410 --> 01:19:50,950
He believes that automakers should ultimately all rely on third-party solutions.

1890
01:19:50,950 --> 01:19:52,639
What's your take on his point of view?

1891
01:19:52,639 --> 01:19:54,979
Yu Kai and I are actually on very good terms.

1892
01:19:54,979 --> 01:19:59,800
I think he's on a really interesting path.

1893
01:19:59,800 --> 01:20:00,860
and hopeful path.

1894
01:20:00,860 --> 01:20:03,420
But perhaps also a very challenging one.

1895
01:20:03,420 --> 01:20:04,520
It all depends on how, in this world...

1896
01:20:04,520 --> 01:20:08,360
Will there ultimately be many or few companies that do both cars and robots?

1897
01:20:08,360 --> 01:20:11,260
The more there are, the broader I think the path forward will be.

1898
01:20:11,260 --> 01:20:12,560
The fewer there are, the more difficult the road ahead will be for Yu Kai.

1899
01:20:12,560 --> 01:20:14,220
So, which way do you lean?

1900
01:20:14,220 --> 01:20:16,300
I'd say it's probably becoming more and more concentrated.

1901
01:20:16,300 --> 01:20:20,260
If you look at things from a user's perspective,

1902
01:20:20,260 --> 01:20:22,720
Because we're looking at it from a company's perspective.

1903
01:20:22,720 --> 01:20:25,780
The user's perspective might just be one of the dozens of perspectives we consider.

1904
01:20:25,780 --> 01:20:29,910
So, from a user's perspective, you'd always feel like you need more car companies.

1905
01:20:29,910 --> 01:20:32,390
and more products from competitors to choose from.

1906
01:20:32,390 --> 01:20:34,130
and more variety in general.

1907
01:20:34,130 --> 01:20:35,940
But in this world,

1908
01:20:35,940 --> 01:20:37,700
But the thing is, cars are just so complex.

1909
01:20:37,700 --> 01:20:39,340
If it were a relatively simple matter,

1910
01:20:39,340 --> 01:20:42,160
I think it will quickly reach a point of unification.

1911
01:20:42,160 --> 01:20:44,240
When I say 'consolidated,' I'm talking about Apple's iPhone.

1912
01:20:44,240 --> 01:20:46,549
I know this might not sound very nice to say,

1913
01:20:46,549 --> 01:20:48,189
I mean, for the last few generations,

1914
01:20:48,189 --> 01:20:49,649
the changes in Apple's phones haven't been that significant.

1915
01:20:49,649 --> 01:20:51,229
but it stays incredibly stable nonetheless.

1916
01:20:51,229 --> 01:20:52,069
Exactly.

1917
01:20:52,069 --> 01:20:53,249
and the shifts in the entire smartphone market.

1918
01:20:53,249 --> 01:20:56,300
Nowadays, the only time I buy a new phone is when my old one just breaks.

1919
01:20:56,300 --> 01:20:59,220
Otherwise, it's not like I'm getting a new phone just because it has some new feature I need.

1920
01:20:59,220 --> 01:21:01,000
that I absolutely have to go and buy a new one.

1921
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:04,080
But the car industry is nowhere near that point yet.

1922
01:21:04,080 --> 01:21:07,560
In fact, I believe that in the future, we could be spending 100 billion a year on R&D.

1923
01:21:07,560 --> 01:21:10,809
the value of continuous, massive innovation is undeniable.

1924
01:21:10,809 --> 01:21:13,920
In a field like this,

1925
01:21:13,920 --> 01:21:15,520
I think, for traditional car companies in the past,

1926
01:21:15,520 --> 01:21:17,660
In fact, a lot of companies don't do their own R&D.

1927
01:21:17,660 --> 01:21:19,180
He said, if you take a look at these car companies,

1928
01:21:19,180 --> 01:21:20,280
I mean, they spend a ton of money.

1929
01:21:20,280 --> 01:21:21,460
He said they spend a ton of money.

1930
01:21:21,460 --> 01:21:22,380
And they have a massive workforce.

1931
01:21:22,380 --> 01:21:24,080
But I'm saying if they don't do their own R&D...

1932
01:21:24,080 --> 01:21:29,490
So, you're saying it's wrong for them to do just integration?

1933
01:21:29,490 --> 01:21:30,090
And you go for in-house development,

1934
01:21:30,090 --> 01:21:31,750
In reality, you'll find that doing it yourself is an even worse idea.

1935
01:21:31,750 --> 01:21:33,310
Because cars are incredibly complex.

1936
01:21:33,310 --> 01:21:35,070
There are just so, so many things you have to develop.

1937
01:21:35,070 --> 01:21:37,910
So, it's better to just admit that there are some areas where you're just not built for it.

1938
01:21:37,910 --> 01:21:40,130
It's better to just partner with A, or partner with B.

1939
01:21:40,130 --> 01:21:41,190
That's a fair point.

1940
01:21:41,190 --> 01:21:42,650
But, look at it from another angle.

1941
01:21:42,650 --> 01:21:45,410
It all comes down to whether this is a strategy for your cars, or just a tactic.

1942
01:21:45,410 --> 01:21:48,200
If it's a tactic, then you shouldn't be developing it in-house.

1943
01:21:48,200 --> 01:21:50,520
If it's a strategic move, then you have to do it in-house. This brings us back to a fundamental question.

1944
01:21:50,520 --> 01:21:53,100
Like you were asking at the very beginning,

1945
01:21:53,100 --> 01:21:54,640
So, let's say in 10 years,

1946
01:21:54,640 --> 01:21:57,560
For example, in ten years, will our vehicle software make up 50% of the car's total value?

1947
01:21:58,110 --> 01:22:00,470
If it does, what about those one or two Tier 1 suppliers?

1948
01:22:00,470 --> 01:22:03,230
So, does that mean we can help our partners get to that 50% mark?

1949
01:22:03,230 --> 01:22:04,570
Of course, they're hoping for that.

1950
01:22:04,570 --> 01:22:05,360
Right.

1951
01:22:05,360 --> 01:22:08,540
I think it's possible, but maybe not.

1952
01:22:08,540 --> 01:22:12,480
In the automotive industry, we have a concept known as cross-domain fusion.

1953
01:22:12,930 --> 01:22:15,070
It's about merging a lot of different capabilities together.

1954
01:22:15,070 --> 01:22:16,650
There's the hardware and the software,

1955
01:22:16,650 --> 01:22:20,989
There's manufacturing, design, services, and operations.

1956
01:22:20,989 --> 01:22:24,120
And all of these things are completely different and unrelated.

1957
01:22:24,120 --> 01:22:26,060
And then you have to merge them all together.

1958
01:22:26,060 --> 01:22:27,040
A lot of people say,

1959
01:22:27,040 --> 01:22:28,240
So, how do you actually bring all that together?

1960
01:22:28,240 --> 01:22:29,040
For example...

1961
01:22:29,040 --> 01:22:32,040
So why do we always hear about all these 'all-in-one' systems in the car industry?

1962
01:22:32,040 --> 01:22:34,700
It's basically just about combining different things into one.

1963
01:22:34,700 --> 01:22:37,960
But in software, this idea of 'n-in-one' or 'all-in-one'...

1964
01:22:37,960 --> 01:22:44,819
It might integrate dozens of different capabilities, and the entire systems you have to put together for that are completely different.

1965
01:22:44,819 --> 01:22:48,860
This isn't something a single company can pull off.

1966
01:22:48,860 --> 01:22:52,440
For instance, let's say you used to be able to work with three companies and get the job done.

1967
01:22:52,440 --> 01:22:55,320
it was easy to come together and provide a total solution.

1968
01:22:55,320 --> 01:22:58,520
But sorry, now you have to work with 300 companies.

1969
01:22:58,520 --> 01:23:00,000
to deliver a personalized solution.

1970
01:23:00,000 --> 01:23:01,580
and it's going to be incredibly painful.

1971
01:23:01,580 --> 01:23:02,680
XPeng's path,

1972
01:23:02,680 --> 01:23:06,299
Both our path and Kai Yu's path with Horizon Robotics could lead to success.

1973
01:23:06,299 --> 01:23:07,319
But as for what happens today, I can't say for sure.

1974
01:23:07,319 --> 01:23:09,659
I think Yu Kai has done a great job with his company, Horizon Robotics.

1975
01:23:09,659 --> 01:23:10,779
And their products are great, too.

1976
01:23:10,779 --> 01:23:12,639
On that point, I absolutely agree.

1977
01:23:12,639 --> 01:23:14,430
But, what I want to say is...

1978
01:23:14,430 --> 01:23:17,090
Ultimately, the endgame for this strategy...

1979
01:23:17,090 --> 01:23:18,910
Or rather, what's the foreseeable endgame here?

1980
01:23:18,910 --> 01:23:22,160
So, looking at cars or robots, how many companies do you think will ultimately consolidate the market?

1981
01:23:22,160 --> 01:23:24,580
This is something that spans several years, possibly decades.

1982
01:23:24,580 --> 01:23:26,440
I think the differences between companies are just too vast.

1983
01:23:26,440 --> 01:23:28,439
Let's put the robots aside for a moment.

1984
01:23:28,439 --> 01:23:32,299
I've always said that by 2030, China will probably only have five major car companies left.

1985
01:23:32,299 --> 01:23:35,090
Now, that's not to say the other car companies will go out of business.

1986
01:23:35,090 --> 01:23:36,250
But what I want to say is,

1987
01:23:36,250 --> 01:23:37,170
is a decline in scale.

1988
01:23:37,170 --> 01:23:40,890
will make it increasingly harder to enter this kind of ultra-high-intensity competition.

1989
01:23:40,890 --> 01:23:43,250
So, have you managed to swim out of that sea of blood yet?

1990
01:23:43,250 --> 01:23:44,530
I think we're all still in the water, just swimming.

1991
01:23:44,530 --> 01:23:47,510
So have I? I don't think so.

1992
01:23:47,510 --> 01:23:49,150
No. And I don't think anyone has made it out either.

1993
01:23:49,150 --> 01:23:50,590
By my definition...

1994
01:23:50,590 --> 01:23:53,470
First of all, don't even ask me what my definition is.

1995
01:23:53,470 --> 01:23:55,450
In my opinion, no one has really broken through yet.

1996
01:23:55,450 --> 01:23:57,809
The challenge with robotics will be ten times that, right?

1997
01:23:57,809 --> 01:24:00,729
I think robotics, on the other hand, might actually be a bit better.

1998
01:24:00,729 --> 01:24:05,470
Because the potential for homogeneous, cut-throat competition in the robotics space is lower.

1999
01:24:05,470 --> 01:24:07,559
First, the software is going to be incredibly valuable.

2000
01:24:07,559 --> 01:24:08,919
And on that point, I think everyone agrees.

2001
01:24:08,919 --> 01:24:11,559
Secondly, I don't believe there's a really good open-source option out there.

2002
01:24:11,559 --> 01:24:14,630
that can help a robotics company build great software.

2003
01:24:14,630 --> 01:24:16,590
So, what does a typical day look like for you?

2004
01:24:16,590 --> 01:24:18,910
I guess it's probably the same as for many other entrepreneurs.

2005
01:24:18,910 --> 01:24:21,740
I start my day a bit on the later side,

2006
01:24:21,740 --> 01:24:23,340
and I get home very late.

2007
01:24:23,340 --> 01:24:25,480
And every day, there are a ton of decisions to be made.

2008
01:24:25,480 --> 01:24:27,480
Most of the expectations are for things to move very quickly.

2009
01:24:27,480 --> 01:24:29,540
I'm constantly talking and thinking things through.

2010
01:24:29,540 --> 01:24:31,020
So that's a typical day.

2011
01:24:31,020 --> 01:24:32,480
So, what have you been reading lately?

2012
01:24:32,480 --> 01:24:35,770
I don't really read books that are too specific these days.

2013
01:24:35,770 --> 01:24:40,430
I have a lot of books on my desk, but I might just flip through a chapter and move on.

2014
01:24:40,430 --> 01:24:40,810
Uh...

2015
01:24:40,810 --> 01:24:44,400
I feel like the principles you find in books...

2016
01:24:44,400 --> 01:24:46,520
But in the current landscape, everything is changing way too fast.

2017
01:24:46,520 --> 01:24:47,780
It's just hard to generalize.

2018
01:24:47,780 --> 01:24:50,520
By the time an author finishes writing a book and it goes to print,

2019
01:24:50,520 --> 01:24:52,490
the world might have already changed by another 10%.

2020
01:24:52,490 --> 01:24:55,050
Let's assume, within the scope of his book,

2021
01:24:55,050 --> 01:24:59,820
That's why I think reading is something you should do when the environment is more stable.

2022
01:24:59,820 --> 01:25:00,840
How do you absorb knowledge?

2023
01:25:00,840 --> 01:25:02,340
Actually, absorbing knowledge is the easiest part.

2024
01:25:02,340 --> 01:25:05,040
I think you absorb it through practice.

2025
01:25:05,040 --> 01:25:06,820
I used to have my own way of summing up how to absorb knowledge.

2026
01:25:06,820 --> 01:25:07,820
Read ten thousand books,

2027
01:25:07,820 --> 01:25:09,020
travel ten thousand miles,

2028
01:25:09,020 --> 01:25:10,420
and having countless conversations.

2029
01:25:10,420 --> 01:25:14,980
to roll up your sleeves countless times, and to put it into practice.

2030
01:25:14,980 --> 01:25:18,800
I think the most important thing right now is, for many of the things you see...

2031
01:25:18,800 --> 01:25:22,010
how to operate on a big enough platform

2032
01:25:22,010 --> 01:25:23,850
and execute on your rapid iteration cycles.

2033
01:25:23,850 --> 01:25:26,960
Internally, companies are organized around the PDCA cycle.

2034
01:25:26,960 --> 01:25:31,020
But in an AI system, you have to rely on fully automated cycles.

2035
01:25:31,020 --> 01:25:33,650
The 'C' in PTC can't even be done.

2036
01:25:33,650 --> 01:25:37,790
Essentially, it should minimize human involvement at every single stage.

2037
01:25:37,790 --> 01:25:43,800
Looking back, are there any decisions you regret?

2038
01:25:46,360 --> 01:25:49,680
In this world, there's no need to dwell on decisions you regret.

2039
01:25:52,060 --> 01:25:54,490
Because you make too many mistakes.

2040
01:25:54,650 --> 01:25:56,530
Why regret making a mistake?

2041
01:25:56,530 --> 01:25:58,050
We often feel that...

2042
01:25:58,050 --> 01:26:00,050
So, something we did back then was a mistake.

2043
01:26:00,050 --> 01:26:02,540
So let's think about why it was the wrong move back then.

2044
01:26:02,980 --> 01:26:04,280
But there's no need for regret.
